<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Admits Mishandling Civil Service Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe government today
admitted it mishandled the country's biggest nationwide strike by
civil servants last August which cost the country over 100
million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Public Service, Labor and Social Welfare Minister Florence
Chitauro, who for some time was principal government negotiator,
said apparent lack of negotiating skills had been observed on the
part of the government.
</P>
<P>
''During the strike, it was also observed that the lack of
skills was also with the employer. Everybody needs to be trained
on how to handle and appreciate labor relations,'' Chitauro said
when opening a three-day workshop on collective bargaining in the
public sector.
</P>
<P>
A two-week work stoppage by government workers paralyzed
delivery of essential services and the government responded to
the industrial action by dismissing the bulk of the over 162,000
employees, refusing to enter into any dialogue with them until
they resumed work.
</P>
<P>
Hardline stances adopted by both the government and the
workers resulted in a lot of suffering for the public and have
been widely criticized.
</P>
<P>
The strike had brought to the fore the absence of laid down
procedures, poor communication, poor organization and poor
representative structure on the part of associations, the
minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
