<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Foreign Minister Visits Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister
Farez Boueiz arrived here today to coordinate stances with Syria
on regional issues.
</P>
<P>
He was greeted at the Syrian-Lebanese border point by his
Syrian counterpart Farouq Al-Shara and other senior officials of
the Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival on his official visit, Boueiz said in a statement
that he will consult with the Syrian foreign minister about the
current regional developments, Israel's practices after having
long delayed the Middle East peace process and the future
prospects of the peace march as well.
</P>
<P>
According to well-informed Syrian sources, the Lebanese-Syrian
talks will cover the latest developments in the Middle East in
general.
</P>
<P>
The passenger bus explosion in the Syrian capital of Damascus
on December 31 will be also be dealt with in particular, said
the sources.
</P>
<P>
Syria claims that the Damascus terrorist act was perpetrated
by Israeli intelligence agents with the object of separating the
Syrian and Lebanese tracks and undermining the peace
process. However, Israel has denied any involvement in the
accident.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, the Syrian and Lebanese foreign ministers
will seek to unify their views, and coordinate their stances in
facing the challenges posed by Israeli extremist and intransigent
policies, the same sources added.
</P>
<P>
Farez Boueiz' trip is the first one by a senior Lebanese
official to Syria since the Damascus bombing, which killed nine
people and wounded some 40 others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
