<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EC/World Bank to Host Preparatory Donors Meeting for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission(EC) and
the World Bank are to hold a conference in Brussels on January 9
and 10 in preparation for a meeting, set for early March, of
donors providing aid for reconstruction in Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
According to the Commission, the emergency projects begun in
1996 must be pursued, while developing longer-term objectives for
the country's reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
After promising 1.2 billion US dollars at the 1996 donors
conference, of which 720 million US dollars has actually been paid,
donors are expected to commit to 1.4 billion US dollars for 1997,
according to Commission sources.
</P>
<P>
Initial funding was used to renovate several rail lines and to
re-open Sarajevo's commercial airport. Some 15,000 housing units
are under construction and basic services such as electricity and
running water have been re-established.
</P>
<P>
However, the Commission said, with a significant amount of this
last year's pledges already spent or earmarked for specific
projects, fresh money would be needed in time to prevent delays in
Bosnia's reconstruction program.
</P>
<P>
Industrial production in Bosnia reportedly doubled over the
past year, but is still 10 to 15 percent below pre-war levels.
Unemployment, which stood at 90 percent in December 1995, has
fallen significantly, but half of the working population is still
without a job. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
