<HEADLINE> China Dominates World Cup Short-Course Swimming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Hosts China took the limelight
by capturing a total of seven golds out of the 17 on offer here
Wednesday at the World Cup Short-Course Swimming tournament.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing leg was the second of the eight-stop World Cup
series this year, with two in Asia -- Hong Kong and Beijing -- and
six in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese female swimmers made a more brilliant performance
than their male counterparts as they clinched six out of eight
titles in the women's competitions.
</P>
<P>
The two lady's crowns slipped from the hosts hands went to
Olympic Champion Claudia Poll of Costa Rica in the 200-meter
freestyle and Lin Chi-chan of Chinese Taipei in the 800-meter
freestyle.
</P>
<P>
Poll, 24, Olympic gold-medalist in the women's 200-meter
freestyle, again proved the superiority in her speciality. She
clocked 1:57.02 in the 200m freestyle, 1.60 seconds short of her
own world record of 1:55.42 set at the World Cup Short-Course
Championships in Rio De Janeiro in December, 1995.
</P>
<P>
"I am satisfied with the results," Poll said, "I haven't
participated in the international competition for more than five
months." the 1.91-meter-tall slim girl from the tiny South
American country said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
"The Hong Kong competitions was her first major international
appearance since the Atlanta Olympic Games." said Francisco Ricos,
who have coached the Costa Rican swimmer for 17 years.
</P>
<P>
Lin came out just a "underdog", but she surprisingly dashed the
Poll's dream of winning the second gold of the night by taking
away the title of 800m freestyle.
</P>
<P>
She touched the pad in 8:30.35, just 0.63 seconds ahead of more
fancied rival Poll at 8:30.98.
</P>
<P>
Butterfly specialist Liu Limin of China grabbed the 100m gold
in her strong event. The world record-holder finished the distance
at 59.07, 0.39 shy of her own best time.
</P>
<P>
"She had a two-month layoff after the Olympic Games," said
Liu's coach Zhao Ge, "She is now back on her normal form."
</P>
<P>
Liu bagged two silvers for China in Atlanta, in the 100m
butterfly and 4X100m freestyle.
</P>
<P>
Another 17 golds will offer on Thursday. The next leg
competitions will be held in Espoo, Finland through January 22 to
23. 
</P>
</TEXT>
