<HEADLINE> France Remembers Mitterrand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The French people today
commemorated the first anniversary of the death of President
Francois Mitterrand, who ruled France for 14 years.
</P>
<P>
President Jacques Chirac asked his chief of staff, Admiral
Jean-Luc Delaunay, to place a wreath on the tomb of the late
president, in Jarnac in the central department of Charente.
</P>
<P>
People early this morning began placing roses -- the flower for
commemorating the dead in France -- at 9 Avenue Frederic le Play,
in Paris, where Mitterrand died a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist Party's first secretary, Lionel Jospin, said that
although the assessment by socialists of their former leader was
varied, they had a "common will to pay homage to Francois
Mitterrand, to prolong and relaunch the socialist force."
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party daily,l'Humanite, said in its editorial
that the anniversary marked the beginning of a debate over the
future of the leftist forces in France.
</P>
<P>
The daily, Liberation, said that one year after he died,
Mitterrand seemed to have only a "remote relationship with the
politics and socialism" of France. He was more talked about by
"the big circulation press than in the socialist conclaves."
</P>
<P>
Other newspapers discussed stories about his cancer, and
revelations in books about his last days of presidency.
</P>
<P>
As for descriptions of Mitterrand, they range from
machiavellian to the psychological portrait in the books of
Francois Mauriac. 
</P>
</TEXT>
