<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflations Rate Down in Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Athens, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Greece's inflations rate at the
end of 1996 was running at 7.5 percent against 8.1 percent at the
end of 1995, the National Statistics Service (ESYE) announced
today.
</P>
<P>
Inflation broke the 8 percent barrier in November for the first
time in 25 years, falling to an annual 7.7 percent against 8.3
percent in the preceding month of October.
</P>
<P>
ESYE attributed the decline in inflation to a 0.9 percent
increase in the cost-of-living index in December against a 1.0
percent rise in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
More specifically, price increases were recorded in December in
fish, vegetables and "served food", beverages, coffee, barbershops
and beauty parlors, "served drinks" and taxi fares due to the
Christmas bonus. Long-distance bus fares also rose. Decreases in
the prices of fruit and petrol counterbalanced the increases to a
degree. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
