<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Prime Minister Leaves for Asia Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister John Major
started an Asia tour to India, Pakistan and Bangladesh earlier
today in an effort to promote trade cooperation with these
countries.
</P>
<P>
During the week-long trip, Major is scheduled to hold separate
talks with Indian Prime Minister Deve Gowda, Bangladesh Prime
Minister Sheikh Hasina and Pakistan's caretaker Prime Minister
Meraj Khalid to exchange views of common interest.
</P>
<P>
Major is taking one of the largest delegation of British
business and industry leaders, highlighting the commercial
significance of his last foreign trip before the general election.
</P>
<P>
One government source said that the growing importance of India
as Britain's major trading partner means the visit makes good
commercial sense.
</P>
<P>
"This is about cementing relationships and opening doors for
the future," he said, adding British trade with India has almost
doubled over the past four years to around 3.5 billion pounds
(5.95 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
British Trade and Industry Secretary Ian Lang, who is
traveling with Major, said earlier that "India and Pakistan
represent two of our key markets" in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
