<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York City Trial Judges to Undergo Annual </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Under a new system which will
be introduced for the first time in New York City courts, many
trial judges will now undergo annual evaluations and could face
demotion.
</P>
<P>
The review system covers only the so-called acting justices,
who are drawn primarily from the criminal and civil courts for
newable one-year appointments to the State Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
The annual evaluation will be carried out by senior judges.
Those judges who handle too few cases, make too many mistakes or
generate too many complaints could face demotion.
</P>
<P>
The plan comes after a year in which a number of judges through
the New York State came under withering attacks for wrongheaded
rulings and lenient treatment of defendants.
</P>
<P>
Under the new system, a panel of senior administrative judges
from the State office of Court Administration will review the
performance of acting justices with the administrative judges in
each county. The justices' workload, courtroom behavior and legal
reasoning will all be part of the evaluation. The panel will make
a recommendation to the chief administrative judge of the New York
State court system, who will make the final decision on whether
the acting justice should be appointed for another year.
</P>
<P>
In the past, judges were reviewed informally, and the standards
of evaluation were usually unknown.
</P>
<P>
"This is a merit-based system, and it looks at performance,"
Jonathan Lippman, chief judge of the New York State court system
was quoted today by the New York Times as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
