<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philips to Become Passive Minority Shareholder in Grundig </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Dutch electronic concern
Philips announced today it had decided to further disconnect
itself from Grundig to become a passive minority shareholder in
the German company.
</P>
<P>
It said that the background to this decision was twofold: the
single brand policy that Philips is moving towards, particularly
in the markets for sound and vision, and the negative returns on
its investment in Grundig AG.
</P>
<P>
Philips has already announced the implementation of the single
brand policy in the United States by the Philips-Magnavox dual
branding.
</P>
<P>
The next step, the company said, was to implement this policy
in Europe. "As a consequence, the Grundig brand name was no longer
vital for Philips," it said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Philips started negotiations with the Max Grundig
Foundation to unwind the contractual relationship between Philips
and the Foundation.
</P>
<P>
Philips said that the company, no longer being in control,
would deconsolidate Grundig AG December 31, 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
