<HEADLINE> UNICEF Worries About Children at Risk in Eastern Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan children in eastern Zaire
are starving because of the lack of food, the United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) said here today.
</P>
<P>
In a press release, UNICEF expressed deep concern at the
deteriorating condition of the Rwandan refugees and internally
displaced people in eastern Zaire.
</P>
<P>
It quoted the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees
(UNHCR) as saying that some 120,000 refugees and displaced people
have settled in Tingi-Tingi, seven kilometers southeast of Lubutu,
and a further 60,000 people are sheltering in Amisi, 70 kilometers
southeast of Lubutu. Most of them are women and children. The
mortality rate in the area has increased dramatically in the last
three days.
</P>
<P>
On January 6, 23 deaths were reported, 12 of whom were children
under five, according to UNICEF. On average, in the preceding
days, three children died every day. Reports from Amisi suggest
that the condition of the people there could be even worse, UNICEF
said.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF noted that the lack of food and the outbreak of
disceases like diarrhea and malaria are major causes of the rising
death rate. It said, "Refugees are weak and vulnerable to disease
after a long journey with little sustenance. Mothers are often too
poorly-nourished to breastfeed their babies or to give adequate
care to their children."
</P>
<P>
Besides refugees, local communities are also affected by the
present lack of food, said UNICEF, adding that the problem is
going worse because of difficulties in delivering food to the
area, where there is only a small airstrip and where roads are
often inaccessible.
</P>
<P>
A UNICEF-chartered plane is shuttling three times a day between
Kisangani and Lubutu, carrying urgently needed supplies of high
protein food for malnourished children and therapeutic milk to
supplement existing stocks at Lubutu, UNICEF said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
