<HEADLINE> Labor Is Confident of Winning Election, Says Blair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Tony Blair, British Opposition
leader, said today that Labor is confident of winning the general
election due by May 22.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference similar to a presidential-style one
by Prime Minister John Major on Tuesday that Labor's confidence
"is born of our unity and our strength of purpose".
</P>
<P>
It is also born of "the incompetence of the opposition and its
weak leadership, the people coming to us from all walks of life
and above all an agreed set of policies that meet the needs of the
people...", Blair added.
</P>
<P>
While launching the election campaign, Blair spared no efforts
to condemn  Major as "an uncertain prime minister" who could not
hold his party together.
</P>
<P>
"In uncertain times Britain can not afford an uncertain Prime
Minister. And Britain cannot afford as its Government a party
incapable of being led," he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to his own party, Blair said, Labor is now "a party
in the center ground of British politics, that will govern in the
center ground too".
</P>
<P>
"For the first time in a generation, Labor goes into a general
election with real confidence," he added.
</P>
<P>
Blair reiterated that education, designed to give Britain the
skilled workforce needed for the 21st century, would be the key
concern of his government.
</P>
<P>
On the question of personal taxation, which the most British
people are concerned for, Blair did not imply whether he would
increase or not, if he comes to power.
</P>
<P>
But he declined to rule out the possibility that taxes might
rise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
