<HEADLINE> UK New Car Sales Reach 7-Year High in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- New car sales in Britain jumped
through two million last year to their highest level for seven
years and was 4.12 percent ahead of the 1995 total, according to
figures released Tuesday by the Society of Motor Manufacturers and
Traders (SMMT).
</P>
<P>
Total sales for the year were 2.03 million, the third highest
level on record and not far below the 1989 peak of 2.3 million
units.
</P>
<P>
The SMMT said that the market was helped by a buoyant December
in which new car sales rose 9.23 percent compared with the same
month in 1995, to more than 78,000.
</P>
<P>
However, the society described the number of private sales as
disappointing and said the sales recovery was still patchy.
</P>
<P>
Sales to private buyers rose only 2.3 percent in 1996 and as a
percentage fell from 47 percent in 1995 to 46 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Although the numbers of private buyers were 14 percent higher
last month than the same month in 1995, this year could prove
tricky as uncertainty was triggered by the general election.
</P>
<P>
The SMMT predicted that demand this year may grow by only
between one and two percent, to a maximum 2.07 million units.
</P>
</TEXT>
