<HEADLINE> Egypt, Jordan Urge Implementing Signed Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian and Jordanian heads of
state today stressed that just and comprehensive peace in the
Mideast should be achieved by implementing all the signed
agreements.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and King Hussein of Jordan who
arrived in the southern city of Aswan earlier today for a
lightning visit, were speaking at a press conference at the end of
their meeting.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary that just peace be attained so that stability
would prevail in the region and cooperation can be established in
the different domains," Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Egypt and Jordan, basic partners in the peace
process, are awaiting what would come out of the ongoing
negotiations between the Palestinians and the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Egyptian president has warned that Israel's
insistence on a hardline policy would mean cutting relations with
all Arab countries and bring the peace process to zero point.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak expressed hope that Palestinians and Israelis could
reach an agreement that "would satisfy both peoples" and attain a
lasting solution that is based on sound foundations.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations on Israeli troop redeployment in Hebron itself
have already been concluded, but the last obstacle blocking the
signing of the deal centered on the timetable for further Israeli
troop pullbacks from the rural areas of West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders preceded their meeting with a motorcade tour of
Aswan, 900 kilometers south of Cairo, and then visited the site
of the High Dam, which was completed in 1970.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, King Hussein and Mubarak also met with the
chief editors of Egyptian newspapers during a 45-minute session,
which was also attended by senior Egyptian and Jordanian officials.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein's visit came within the framework of continued
contacts which the Egyptian president makes with Arab leaders to
consolidate common Arab action.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Jordan are the only two Arab countries to have signed
peace treaties with Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
