<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Expresses Support to Somali Peace Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Prime Minister
Meles Zenawi today told the 26 Somali political movements who
recently formed a National Salvation Council here that his
country will support the implementation of their new peace
accord.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Ethiopian Foreign Ministry was quoted by
the Ethiopian News Agency as saying that the Ethiopian prime
minister made the remarks when he was talking with leaders of the
26 Somali political movements at his office.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Meles said Ethiopia is committed to working
with the newly established National Salvation Council and with
the Somali people with a view to forging international assistance
towards ensuring the realization of the new peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Meles said Ethiopia is working for the restoration of peace
and stability in Somalia not only because it was mandated by the
Organization of African Unity and the Inter-Governmental
Authority on Development, but also the present political crisis
in that country affects Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
He also said the formation of a legitimate government in
Somalia will help foster the socio-economic activities of the
peoples of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The National Salvation Council of Somalia was formed on
January 3 following six-week high level consultative meeting of
leaders of the 26 Somali political movements at Sodere, about 120 km
southeast of Addis Ababa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
