<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wide Gap Exists Over Clinching Hebron Deal: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 8 (Xinhua) -- While U.S. envoy Dennis Ross
continued his mediation today, Palestinian officials said wide
gap still exists between the Palestinians and Israelis over
signing the long-delayed Hebron agreement.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who held five-hour talks with Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat Tuesday night, today held another round of talks with
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu to explore ways to
bridge the gap.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials described the talks as hitting a snag
as Israel refused to honor the Oslo accords by delaying further
troop redeployments in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to European visitors today, Arafat called on
European Union to exert pressure on Israel to honor the signed
agreements.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader reportedly has rejected the
U.S. compromise proposal over the timetable for further Israeli
troop pullbacks during his meeting with Ross.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian minister Marwan Knafani described the Arafat-Ross
meeting Tuesday night as "extremely tense," warning that the
Israeli position could destroy all hopes for reaching a Hebron
deal. Due to the deadlock, a scheduled summit between Arafat and
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu was cancelled in the
last minute.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel renews its accusation of the Palestinian
side for refusing to sign the Hebron deal. Moshe Fogel, Director
of the Government Press Office and Israel's spokesman on the
Hebron talks, blamed Arafat for delaying conclusion of the
Hebron deal in order to gain international support.
</P>
<P>
Fogel said the Hebron deal had been virtually sealed for the
past six weeks, it could not be signed until now just because
the Palestinian side tried to raise other issues beyond the
Hebron redeployment.
</P>
<P>
He called on Arafat to sign the Hebron deal first in order to
push forward the peace process. "Our feeling is that Mr. Arafat
is not in rush, and it is really up to him when we can go
forward," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking Tuesday night, Netanyahu said it would become clear
very soon if the Hebron deal could be reached. He demanded the
Palestinian side to show good will to reach the Hebron deal.
</P>
<P>
The last obstacle blocking the signing of a deal centered on
the timetable for further Israeli troop pullbacks from rural
areas of the West Bank, which should be completed by September
this year under the Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu only promises to complete further troop pullbacks
by spring 1999, but Arafat insists on Israel's accurate
implementation of the Oslo accords which call for the completion
of the process by September this year. Ross is suggesting a
compromise date of summer 1998.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that Netanyahu is seeking delay of further
pullbacks in order to retain more territorial cards pending the
upcoming final-status talks with the Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-08 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Israelis Killed in Clashes With Hezbollah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Two Israeli soldiers were killed
and six others wounded in an attack by guerrillas of the Lebanese
pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, in the Israeli
self-proclaimed "security zone" in south Lebanon this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Security sources in south Lebanon reported that the casualties,
the heaviest suffered by the 1,000-strong Israeli forces in south
Lebanon since this year, has not been officially confirmed by the
Israeli side.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued in Beirut tonight, the Islamic
Resistance, the military wing of Hezbollah, announced that its
guerrillas thwarted an infiltrating attempt of an Israeli
commandos force later this afternoon into an area controlled by
the Shiite fundamentalist party.
</P>
<P>
It said that the Israeli force was trying to advance from an
outpost near Deir Siryan village in the occupied border strip and
was blocked by the guerrillas at the Litan River basin.
</P>
<P>
A fierce clash erupted between the Israeli force and the
guerrillas in which several Israeli soldiers were killed or
wounded, said the Hezbollah statement.
</P>
<P>
Security sources in the area said that the Israeli occupation
forces fired heavy artilleries tonight at the Litan river basin
as well as vicinities of south Lebanese villages in the nearby
areas.
</P>
<P>
In retaliation for an earlier bombing attack on an Israeli
patrol, Israeli forces opened violent artillery fire at guerrilla
bases of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Police sources in south Lebanon reported that Israeli
artillery fired more than 150 shells at Hezbollah targets in
Iglim Al-Toffah and Western Beqaa since this morning without
causing casualties.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Resistance, the military wing of Hezbollah,
announced that one squad of its fighters detonated a mine at
6:00 a.m. (0400 GMT), targeting an Israeli force attempting to
advance toward Abu Rashid village.
</P>
<P>
The guerrilla group said that five Israeli soldiers were
wounded in the explosion, adding that they were evacuated by
Israeli military helicopters from the battle scene.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Radio confirmed the attack taking place in the eastern
sector of the Israeli self-carved buffer zone in south Lebanon,
claiming that three Israeli soldiers were wounded, including one
in serious situation.
</P>
<P>
Today's escalation in south Lebanon came just as a five-nation
committee monitoring a limited truce on the Lebanese-Israeli
border wound up this morning its first meeting in 1997 without
blaming anyone for alleged cease-fire breaches just before the
year end.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued at the end of the meeting, the
cease-fire monitoring committee urged the Israeli forces and
Lebanese guerrillas, who are engaged in a war of attrition in
south Lebanon, to prevent civilians from being hurt in military
operations.
</P>
<P>
The committee, which comprises France, the United States,
Syria, Lebanon and Israel, was established under a cease-fire
understanding brokered by the U.S. and France last April between
Lebanon and Israel, which put an end to a 17-day Israeli blitz in
south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
It urged the conflicting sides in south Lebanon to keep
their commitment to the April understanding, which warns against
attacks at or from civilians areas, and demands civilians be
kept away from all dangers of military actions.
</P>
<P>
Hit-and-run attacks by Muslim guerrillas and bombardments by
Israeli forces constitute a daily scene on the last active
battlefront of the Arab-Israeli conflict.
</P>
<P>
Israel established the 1,100-square-kilometer "security zone"
in 1985 in a bid to protect the Jewish settlement in northern
Israel from crossing-border attacks by Lebanese
guerrillas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
