<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus to Build New Desalination Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus will build a new
desalination plant to alleviate the fresh water shortage on this
East Mediterranean island country.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced here today by Minister for
Agriculture, Natural Resources and Environment Costas Petrides
after a cabinet meeting which approved the plan.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the plant will be put in tender by
April.
</P>
<P>
This plant, which will supply Nicosia with fresh water, will be
linked with another one now under construction.
</P>
<P>
He added that the water shortage will be eased to a great
extent once these two plants become fully operational.
</P>
<P>
The island relies mainly on rainfall for its water supply.
</P>
<P>
This year the government plans to further cut water supply to
deal with a more severe shortage due to a dry winter.
</P>
<P>
Water supply to the household would be cut by up to 20 percent,
compared with that of 10 per cent last year. Water for farming
purposes would be cut by up to 70 percent in comparison with the
drop of 35 percent the year before, official estimates said.
</P>
</TEXT>
