<HEADLINE> Turkey: Military Build-up in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The "excessive rearmament" of
Greek Cyprus poses a threat to the atmosphere of peace on the
Mediterranean island, the Turkish Foreign Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
This also adversely affects the efforts in finding a solution
to the Cyprus problem, the ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Turkey will not tolerate anything which would harm the security
and territorial interests of the Turkish Cypriots or upset the
Turkish-Greek balance on the strategic island, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement warned the Greek Cypriot side "in the strongest
terms" not to drag the island into "new adventures with unforeseen
consequences."
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Cypriot ministers and representatives of the
Russian state-controlled Rosvoorouzhen company concluded an
agreement in the Cypriot capital of Nicosia on buying S-300
anti-aircraft missiles from Russia.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the Russia-made missiles, with a range of
150 kilometers, will be deployed to protect naval and air bases
under construction on the west coast of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The bases are being built under a joint defense pact between
Cyprus and Greece, agreed in November 1993 to face possible
Turkish threats.
</P>
<P>
The arms deal between Greek Cypriots and Russians has drawn
strong opposition from both Turkish Cypriots and Turkey, the only
country in the world to recognize the self-claimed "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
Northern Cyprus leader Rauf Denktash also accused Moscow of
displaying enmity toward Turks on the island by selling missiles
to Greek Cypriots, warning that Cyprus was on the verge of an
armed conflict.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both NATO allies, are at odds over this
divided island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been unofficially partitioned in 1974 when the
Turkish troops landed on the island and took control of the
northern part following an abortive coup by Greek Cypriots
seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
