<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada, US to Renew Fight over Dairy Product </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The long-running dispute between
Canada and the United States over the former's protection of its
dairy and poultry industries will be renewed soon after a NAFTA
panel ruling in Canada's favor.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is about to start a probe of Canada's new dairy
pricing system to see if it violates the North American Free Trade
Agreement (NAFTA), a report said today.
</P>
<P>
Canada sets the price of milk used in cheese and other dairy
products, which the U.S. says may violate NAFTA and international
trading rules, since some of its production is exported.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. said it believes Canadian cheese exports to the U.S.
was helped by government subsidies ranging from 57 U.S. cents to
95 cents a kilo.
</P>
<P>
At present, Canada is allowed to export up to 70,000 kilos a
year to the U.S. duty free. By the end of last November, it has
exported about 55,000 kilos.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the U.S. is expected to renew its attack on
Canada's protection against dairy and poultry products coming into
the country.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. lost a NAFTA panel ruling last December which found
that Canada's new import duties on dairy and poultry products,
some as high as 350 percent, were legal under NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
Despite the setback, the U.S. dairy and poultry industries are
lobbying the Congress to push pressure on the Clinton
Administration to open up the Canadian market.
</P>
<P>
Dave Redmond, a spokesman for the U.S. House agriculture
chairman Bob Smith, said he expects the Canadian dispute will soon
become a major issue.
</P>
<P>
"It is certainly foremost in the minds of many members of the
committee, especially those with dairy and poultry concerns," he
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government has already indicated that it will not
negotiate any concessions on dairy and poultry even when
international farm talks resume in three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
