<HEADLINE> Kofi Annan to Visit Washington January 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 8 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan will pay a visit to Washington D.C. on January 23, the
first of its kind since he became head of the world organization.
</P>
<P>
In the visit, Annan told reporters, he is going to meet
President Bill Clinton and U.S. legislators. He said he was not
bringing any specific issues to the meeting but would make the
case to U.S. officials "that we all need the United Nations."
</P>
<P>
Diplomats said the issue of reform as well as the related
matter of the 1.3 billion U.S. dollars the United States owes the
United Nations were expected to come up during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Congress has attacked the United Nations as bloated,
inefficient and wasteful and balked at paying off the U.S.
debt to the institution until it is reformed.
</P>
<P>
However, Annan seemed to have different views regarding the
reform. At a meeting with Secretary of State Warren Christopher
Tuesday, Annan emphasized compromise on the issue of reform
instead of large reduction of the U.N. staff.
</P>
<P>
"Governments need to come to an understanding what they want
the United Nations to do," said Fred Eckhard, Annan's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"Sometimes a good leader must also be a good follower," Eckhard
quoted Annan as telling Christopher. 
</P>
</TEXT>
