<HEADLINE> Report: Stolen Remains of Turkish Tycoon Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The corpse of Turkey's late
tycoon Vehbi Koc was believed to have been found after it was
missing for 75 days, Turkish private TV Channel D reported tonight.
</P>
<P>
Some unidentified men called Channel D and claimed that they
had sent Kov's remains back.
</P>
<P>
Then the police did find a body a few yards away from the Koc's
empty grave at the Zincirlikuyu cemetery in Istanbul, the largest
city of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Several people were arrested on suspicion of involvement in the
incident, but no detailed reports are available.
</P>
<P>
Rahmi Koc, son of Vehbi Koc, said that the found body would
soon be identified.
</P>
<P>
The body of Vehbi Koc, Turkey's No.1 businessman, was stolen on
October 24. The incident shocked the whole country and drew strong
condemnation from all walks of life.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish press reported that thieves had robbed the grave to
demand a ransom of 30 or 40 billion Turkish liras (about 300,000
or 400,000 U.S. dollars) from the Koc family.
</P>
<P>
Vehbi Koc, founder of Turkey's largest corporation, Koc
Holding, was 95 when he died in February. 
</P>
