<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton to Meet UN Secretary-General Annan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
will hold his first formal meeting with new United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan on January 23 at the White House, the
White House said today.
</P>
<P>
The issue of U.N. reform and the debt of 1.3 billion U.S.
dollars that the United States owes the U.N. were expected to be
discussed during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said outgoing
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher told Annan during a
meeting Tuesday at the United Nations that the Clinton
administration was confident it could "now begin again to renew a
close relationship" with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said that Clinton wanted to meet Annan at a time
when the Congress was in session so he could meet U.S. legislators
to win their support for paying off the U.S. debt, which is more
than half the 2.3 billion dollars owed to the U.N. by its members.
</P>
<P>
Annan told reporters at the United Nations that he was not
bringing any specific issues to the meeting but would make the
case to U.S. officials "that we all need the United Nations."
</P>
</TEXT>
