<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Adds 11 More Golds in World Cup Short-Course Swimming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Hosts China continued its
momentum at the Beijing Leg World Cup Short-Course swimming
tournament by capturing 11 more golds here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Competing at their own threshold, the Chinese swimmers
accumulated a total of 19 golds in the two-day meet to top the
final medal standings.
</P>
<P>
Last year's sensation here Han Xue of China again showed her
potential in her strongest event by winning the 50m breaststroke.
</P>
<P>
Han, 16, who twice broke the world record of the event in last
year's first two legs competitions in Hong Kong and Beijing,
clocked 31.00 seconds, trimming 0.02 seconds off her mark of 30.98.
</P>
<P>
The Olympian also won a gold in Wednesday's 100m breaststroke.
</P>
<P>
While the Olympic champion Claudia Poll of Costa Rica felt
somewhat disappointed as she failed to extend her gold credit.
</P>
<P>
Chinese teenager Wang Luna burst ahead from behind in the final
spurt to edge Poll in the 400m free. Wang clocked a winning time
of 4:05.45.
</P>
<P>
Poll finished out of top three in the 100m free.
</P>
<P>
Chinese top male swimmer Jiang Chengji took a gold in the men's
50m freestyle at 22.28 while he was edged by Ukraine's Denis
Silantiev into the second in the 100m butterfly.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Jiang, native of Shanghai, finished fourth in
both the men's 50m free and 100m butterfly at the Atlanta Games,
the best results ever for a Chinese male swimmer at the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not in my best form now," said the confident Jiang, who is
expected to do better at the Sydney Olympic Games in 2000. "So I
will try my best." He said.
</P>
<P>
Olympic runner-up Liu Limin extended her medal credit with two
more silvers in the 200m and 50m butterfly.
</P>
<P>
"She now eyes on the eighth National Games and is training hard
for that." said her coach Zhao Ge.
</P>
<P>
Wonda Marcel of the Netherlands became the most golden prolific
swimmer of the two-day competition after grabbing the men's 200m
individual medley.
</P>
<P>
Marcel won two golds on Wednesday, in the 400m IM and 100m IM.
</P>
<P>
Le Jingyi, who claimed the sole Olympic gold for China in in
Atlanta, participated two by-line events at the current
competitions -- 200m free and 50m butterfly.
</P>
<P>
"I took the Beijing Leg only as a adjustment workout." she
said. According to her coach Zhou Min, Le will travel to Italy and
France for two more Short-Course legs, which is slated for early
February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
