<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria's Foreign Currency Reserve Plunges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria's foreign currency
reserves have dropped nearly 60 percent over the past year, to 518
million U.S. dollars, said Lyubomir Filikov, president of the
Bulgarian National Bank, today.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria sold off much of its foreign currency reserve in the
first few months of 1996, down to a level of 667 million dollars
in May, in an effort to curb the drastic devaluation of the
Bulgarian leva against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The payments on Bulgaria's foreign debt, which had amounted to
billions of dollars, also contributed to the decline in the
foreign currency and worsened the weakened economy.
</P>
<P>
The Bulgarian government is expecting the sale of big,
state-run enterprises can improve the situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
