<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Oil Spill Spreading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 9 (Xinhua) -- An oil spill from a wrecked
Russian tanker continued spreading over the Sea of Japan today,
washing ashore along 300 kilometers of coastline and threatening
local economies by damaging marine products and tourism.
</P>
<P>
Patches of oil were found on the coast alongside the towns of
Tango and Amino in Kyoto Prefecture, and nearby Kasumi in Hyogo
Prefecture, about 450 kilometers west of Tokyo, Kyodo News
reported.
</P>
<P>
The oil slick also reached coastal areas near Mikuni in
northern Fukui Prefecture. It was in this area that the front part
of the 13,157-ton Nakhodka ran aground Tuesday after breaking up
on January 2 in stormy waters in the Sea of Japan and drifting,
Kyodo said.
</P>
<P>
The tanker was estimated to have held 17,000 kiloliters (15,300
tons) of fuel oil when the vessel broke up, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The oil has since spread and slicks are scattered from waters
off the Oki Islands in Shimane Prefecture to the sea off the Noto
Peninsula in Ishikawa Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
More oil was likely to come ashore along the coast of Ishikawa
and Fukui prefectures, and the current might spread some to the
northern shore of the Noto Peninsula, the agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
