<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Thierry Dubois, a French skipper joining the Vendee Globe
sailing boat racing across the world, was winched to a helicopter by
Australian marines Wednesday evening, after taking refugee in one of
his two life rafts near the Australian coast. The Australians are
now rescuing a second skipper in the racing, Tony Bullimore of
Britain. A third skipper, Canadian Gerry Roufs, has been missing
since Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The Australians have complained about the cost for the rescue
work and asked the French organizers of the competition to choose a
racing route which is less dangerous.
</P>
<P>
-- Although the Swiss federal authorities were forced to set up a
fund of aid for the victims of Holocaust and their descendants, the
associations in Israel are threatening to boycott all Swiss banking
institutions for the refusal by the Swiss authorities to give back
some 7 billion dollars of properties deposited by Jews in Swiss
banks before and during the World War II.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss government nominated a mediator for facilitating the
search in the banking files about the Jewish properties, but so far
only 45,000 francs (9,000 U.S. dollars) have been repaid to Jews.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. Secretary of State-designate Madeleine Albright
Wednesday confronted Senator Jesse Helms by calling for more
expenditure on U.S. diplomatic activities.
</P>
<P>
-- The South African government of President Nelson Mandela is
planning to outlaw the dogs of war -- former Apartheid white
soldiers turned mercenaries fighting in central African countries
such as Zaire. The Pretoria government is more and more annoyed by
the activities of a Pretoria-based company of guns for hire,
Executive Outcomes, which has been recruiting mercenaries for the
wars in other African states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
