<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin's Temperature Normal, Treatment Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin,
hospitalized overnight with "the first signs" of pneumonia, had a
normal temperature this morning and treatment is being continued.
</P>
<P>
The presidential press service said today that Yeltsin is being
treated for pneumonia with the help of modern antibiotics and is
also undergoing a course of general supportive therapy.
</P>
<P>
"The president had a normal morning temperature," the service
said. It quoted doctors, who examined Yeltsin in Moscow's Central
Clinical Hospital, as saying that "treatment continued as
prescribed."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin also had a 15-minute telephone conversation with
Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin this morning, the press
service said. They discussed "present-day matters of national
importance".
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, 65, underwent heart bypass surgery last November 5,
and returned to the Kremlin in late December. He had been
bedridden in his country residence outside Moscow with a high
temperature since Monday. But Kremlin doctors have insisted that
his current condition was unrelated to the surgery.
</P>
<P>
Russian Public Television's evening news broadcast, "Vremya",
said overnight that doctors had decided to hospitalize Yeltsin for
several days because they had discovered what appeared to be the
first signs of pneumonia after an evening observation of the
president.
</P>
<P>
United States cardiologist Michael DeBakey, a senior adviser
for Yeltsin's November 5 operation, told British BBC radio that
Yeltsin would fully recuperate in one week's time.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's present indisposition was of catarrhal nature and
not dangerous for his heart, DeBakey said. Yeltsin had virtually
recovered fully from the bypass operation, which enabled him to
return to active work, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji on Reemployment, Bankruptcy Issues (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- To help state enterprises
prevail over their current difficult situation, a new competitive
structure should be created to eliminate excessive workers,
standardize bankruptcy and encourage more mergers.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a national conference on the reemployment of workers
from state firms today, Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji recalled the
achievements made in the country's economic sector in the past
year, noting that all the country's macro-economic control targets
have been reached or exceeded.
</P>
<P>
Senior government and CPC leaders Li Lanqing, Wu Bangguo, Ren
Jianxin and Luo Gan were also present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Zhu, also member of the Standing Committee of the Political
Bureau of the Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee,
said the country's economy has been showing a sound development
trend, thanks to the macro-control efforts of the past three years.
</P>
<P>
He noted that in 1996, the government maintained a high
development speed as it simultaneously reduced the inflation rate
to as low as six percent, increased the foreign exchange reserve
to 105 billion US dollars, kept the issue of currency within 100
billion yuan and increased tax collection from industrial and
commercial firms by nearly 106.2 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
He listed the issues of grain production and tackling the
difficult situation challenging state enterprises as two major
tasks for the government's work to improve the economy.
</P>
<P>
China's grain reserve had hit the historic high of 297 billion
kg by the end of 1996, a 68.8 billion kg increase over the
beginning of last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
