<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji on Reemployment, Bankruptcy Issues (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The government has raised the official purchase prices of grain
by 50 percent over the 1995 figures, and domestic grain prices as
well as the prices of imported grains are higher than the
production costs, according to the vice-premier.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, local farmers will not be harmed by low prices, as
the country has experienced good grain harvests for two successive
years, Zhu noted.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the government price hike in grain prices
is one of the main causes of the decrease in profits made by the
country's industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
Other factors responsible for the state firms' hard times
include the official price-rise in the transport and energy
industries, the adoption of the new accounting system, the fact
that individuals are getting a larger share of the distribution,
and also the illegal levies on these firms by local governments,
Zhu noted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he emphasized three bigger problems that are
plaguing state companies: low-level competition due to the
establishment of too many firms of the same kind; market disorder
caused by the influx of smuggled goods; and excessive numbers of
employees and outdated management styles.
</P>
<P>
This year, the government will deal with the state firms'
troubles by strengthening the leadership of these firms, laying
off unnecessary staff, standardizing the procedure of bankruptcy,
and encouraging these companies to merge instead of going
bankrupt, according to Zhu.
</P>
<P>
Bankruptcy should not be conducted by way of sole transfers or
purchases, he said, stressing that in each bankruptcy case, assets
must be cashed in and all employees must be dismissed, while
personnel from the bankrupt firms must be helped to find new jobs
through reemployment programs.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier promised interest-exemption on the inherited
debts for firms that have bought into bankrupt companies, and
reduction or exemption of interest on loans for firms that cannot
go bankrupt and must lay off part of their staff.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that bankruptcy could only take place in 110
pilot cities, disclosing that the government has earmarked no more
than 30 billion yuan to cover the bad loans for banks due to
bankruptcy of state firms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
