<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Panel Essential for Democratic System: Pak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The formation of the Council
for Defense and National Security (CDNS) was "absolutely essential
for the health of parliament and democratic system", said a high
Pakistani official here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference, Caretaker Defense Minister
Shahid Hamid said it would ensure there was no "element of
friction or misunderstanding" between the president and the prime
minister in the future.
</P>
<P>
Hamid said the CDNS would block forever the president to
dissolve the National Assembly under a controversial clause in the
constitution.
</P>
<P>
Four consecutive governments have been dismissed by three
presidents since 1988. President Farooq Leghari last dissolved the
National Assembly and the government of Benazir Bhutto on November
5 last year.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the rational behind the establishment of the CDNS,
which caused objections among most political parties who are busy
preparing for the forthcoming elections on February 3, he said the
president is to take an active part in the affairs of the state.
</P>
<P>
He said the president over the last 10 years had been
participating in matters of vital security issues and hence the
establishment of the CDNS had formalized the arrangement which was
already there.
</P>
<P>
Leghari set up the 10-member council to "aid and advice" the
government on matters including declaration of emergency,
determination of national strategy and fixation of priorities in
terms of over-all national security.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
