<HEADLINE> "One Country, Two Systems" Guaranteed in Macao: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, January 9 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese official
stationed in Macao said tonight that the Portuguese-style
pebble-stone road, portuguese food and the Portuguese buildings in
Macao will not be altered together with the capitalist system for
at least 50 years after 1999 when China resumes the exercise of
sovereignty over Macao. .
</P>
<P>
Wang Qiren, director of the Xinhua News Agency Macao Branch,
told a group of middle and high-ranking civil servants of the
Macao Government, who are to visit Beijing and Harbin City in
northeast China between January 18 and 24, that China takes a
serious attitude towards the implementation of the 'one country,
two systems' policy."
</P>
<P>
"Anything that is not against the basic law of Macao, not
affecting China's resuming the exercise of sovereignty over
Macao, and is in line with the Sino-Portuguese joint declaration,
will not be changed after 1999," he said.
</P>
<P>
Those things include the Portuguese food, pebble-stone roads,
the Macao Governor's Office Building and other Portuguese-style
buildings, as well as those localized laws, according to the
director.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Wang said that the future government of the Macao
Special Administrative Region (MSAR) opens warm arms to the
Macao-born Portuguese, so long as they will stay on in Macao.
</P>
<P>
"The Macao-born Portuguese people have long resided along with
other Macao residents and have done their parts in the development
of Macao," he said. "They can live in harmony with other residents
in Macao so long as they will."
</P>
<P>
The director assured the civil servants that the Chinese side
hopes the civil servants of the Macao Government would stay on and
serve the future MSAR government.
</P>
<P>
Wu Zhiliang, director of the Macao Foundation and one of the
leaders of the visiting group, said that all members of the group
will stride over 1999 and serve the future MSAR government.
</P>
<P>
The group of civil servants' visit is at the invitation of the
Macao Department of the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office of the
State Council. They will visit Beijing University, the Ministry of
Personnel and some other departments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
