<HEADLINE> Newly Appointed Minister in Nepal Expelled by Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 9 (Xinhua) -- A Nepali lawmaker, who was
appointed a cabinet member Wednesday, has been expelled from his
own party, sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
A Central Secretariat meeting of the Nepal Workers and
Peasants' Party (NWPP) has decided to expel Bhakta Bahadur Rokaya
from the party's general membership, charging that he had breached
party discipline.
</P>
<P>
Rokaya, a lower house MP representing the NWPP party, was
appointed state minister for land and soil conservation by Prime
Minister Sher Bahadur Deuba in the latest reshuffle of his cabinet
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Announcing its decision to expel Rokaya, The NWPP party said
Rokaya's involvement in the government is against the party's
official decision to remain in the opposition.
</P>
<P>
The NWPP meeting, held late Wednesday after the cabinet
reshuffle was announced, also decided to demand that the speaker
of the lower house vacate Rokaya's membership in the house.
</P>
<P>
Despite his party's decision to back a no-confidence motion
against the coalition government tabled by the main opposition
Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxist Leninist, CPN-UML),
Rokaya was absent from a special house session on the censure
motion last month.
</P>
<P>
The special house session later rejected the opposition motion
with a vote of 101 in favor and 84 against in the 205-seat House
of Representatives. The motion required a majority of 103 votes to
pass in the house.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
