<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak: Egypt Is Building Future of People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU SIMBEL, southern Egypt, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak said here today the country is going all
out for the benefit of future generations.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, who unveiled a gigantic project aimed at adding
Egypt's arable land by 30 percent and inhabiting the vast expanses
of the south Egypt through digging a canal, made the remarks in
his inauguration speech.
</P>
<P>
The president called the canal a "fortress of security and
peace, a bridge of civilization." He said that it is based on what
has been accumulated for over 30 years of scientific research and
planning.
</P>
<P>
It is rather a "necessity for the whole people" when the
over-crowdedness in the Nile Valley is just getting intolerable
and urbanization is growing to the brink of danger, Mubarak said,
dismissing an accusation that the project is conducted out of
"political motivation."
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Zayed Canal, the so-called New Valley Canal, is located
50 kilometers south of Abu Simbel, the southernmost city of
Egypt. It is just the beginning of an integrated development
project to divert people from the crammed Old Nile Valley to new
communities in the Western Desert in two decades.
</P>
<P>
The irrigation potential is estimated at 2.2 million feddans
(924,000 hectares), equal to the capacity of the Aswan High Dam,
which had added 30 percent to the total cultivable area of Egypt
when its ten-year construction was completed in 1970.
</P>
<P>
Under the first stage, the 30-kilometer-long canal will be able
to irrigate at least half a million feddans (215,000 hectares)
with water diverted from the Aswan High Dam through the Toshki
Depression, where surplus water from the Lake Nasser has been
accumulating.
</P>
<P>
The president, relaxed and smiling, quipped with some of the
VIPs attending the inauguration ceremony and shook hands with some
of the reporters covering the event.
</P>
<P>
"We are building the future of the people of Egypt in the Old
Valley (the Nile Valley) with new communities, agriculture,
industry, tourism, everything (we plan) might happen," Mubarak
told Xinhua immediately after he addressed the inauguration of the
Sheikh Zayed Canal.
</P>
<P>
This canal is planned to be accomplished by installing a pumping
station, the largest in the world, at the Toshki Depression to
pump 30 million cubic meters of water a day from a level of 150
meters to a level of 200 meters into the new canal.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak also reviewed the blueprints for a number of other huge
national projects, known as "Egypt's 21st century project."
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the 30-kilometer-long canal will open the
door to investments in agriculture, land reclamation, industry,
mining, tourism and establishment of integrated urban communities
to absorb the expected population increase till the year 2017,
according to an earlier statement by Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
The integrated works will provide necessary infrastructure to
open the door for industrial, agricultural and tourism schemes on
the map of the New Delta.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri, in his speech, said
the mammoth project would be funded through several means.
</P>
<P>
Of the total 300 billion Egyptian pounds (88 billion
U.S. dollars), the government's contributions, only 20 percent of
the development costs, are limited to providing the area with an
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the bills will be footed by international companies
and Egyptian and Arab private sectors, he said.
</P>
<P>
The ministries of electricity, petroleum, mineral, tourism,
culture, housing and transportation could well generate the
necessary revenues, which cover the 20 percent of the total
investment cost, the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Ganzouri, who has recently inspected Toshki work site twice,
said the new projects, will bring investments to 61.3 million
feddans to cover mining, industrial and agricultural activities.
</P>
<P>
Comprehensive irrigational, geological and agricultural
research and lengthy plans have been conducted over the past
several years by specialized research centers.
</P>
<P>
The first study of the New Valley development project was
conducted in 1960s, but it was reportedly delayed by preparations
for the 1967 Middle East War, popularly know as the "Six-Day War."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
