<HEADLINE> France to Re-examine Army Deployment in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 9 (Xinhua) -- France will re-examine its pattern
of army deployment and the layout of military bases in Africa to
improve their operational capacity, French Defense Minister
Charles Millon said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on local television Europe 1, Millon said: "For an
identical operational efficiency, France could without doubt
re-examine the bases and rotation of soldiers."
</P>
<P>
The defense minister made the suggestion after French troops
clashed earlier this week with mutinous soldiers of the Central
African Republic, which has the largest French military base in
Africa after Djibouti.
</P>
<P>
France would have full consultations with the local governments
which had defense treaties with Paris, before making any changes
to military bases, said Millon.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that the alteration would be "marginal"
and only concern logistical support and troop rotation.
</P>
<P>
France has 8,200 troops deployed in several French-speaking
African countries, considered to be traditional interest zones of
France.
</P>
<P>
Millon made a number of tours in Africa in 1996 and has
reaffirmed France's intention to fully maintain its military
presence in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
