<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Restructure Industrial Setup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Beijing will focus more on
restructuring industry to better cater to local economic
development, according to a vice mayor of the capital city.
</P>
<P>
The move is designed to give an overall boost to the sector's
strength and competitiveness in markets, Yang Anjiang revealed at
an industrial work conference here today. And the comprehensive
strategic improvement will give priority to the rearrangement of
local industrial structure, framework of enterprises, and product
mix, as well as production allocation.
</P>
<P>
More developments are scheduled for the hi-tech,
high-value-added, environmental-friendly, and profitable
industrial projects, rather than the low-efficiency and
high-consumption items such as textiles, leather and plastics,
Yang said.
</P>
<P>
In the urban areas, emphasis will be placed on the development
of commercial and service trades, as well as the re-allocation of
industrial capital and assets.
</P>
<P>
The city intends to develop 75 industrial name-brand products
this year with sales exceeding 50 million yuan each, and 40
surpassing 100 million yuan each. And priority will be given to
technological upgrading for production of 14 name-brand products,
including program-controlled switchboards, color kinescopes made
by a Matsushita-funded business, and computers produced by Legend
Group.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Beijing plans to develop 50 new industrial
products, and put more projects into operation to make more
than 50 new items with sales expected to surpass 10 million
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The city will also promote 10 new industrial technologies,
involving microelectronics information and comprehensive
power-saving for steel-smelting in furnaces. It will also resort
to new technology to improve traditional industrial sectors.
</P>
<P>
The city now has nearly 10,000 industrial enterprises at or
above the county level, with fixed assets reaching 100 billion
yuan. It ranked second in China after Shanghai in its 130 billion
yuan-worth of industrial output value in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Beijing is famous nationwide for its electronics, machinery,
automobiles, metallurgical, and chemical industries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
