<HEADLINE> Nonferrous Metal Futures Turnover in Shanghai Hits $ 27 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Nonferrous metal futures
transactions totaled 230 billion yuan (about 27.7 billion US
dollars) on a volume of over 11 million tons at China's largest
metal futures exchange in Shanghai last year.
</P>
<P>
Trading in metal futures rallied in the second half of 1996,
with the turnover for the last six months up 58 percent over the
first half, according to Zhou Xiaohong, a senior official of the
Shanghai Metals Exchange.
</P>
<P>
The exchange, one of the 15 trial futures bourses approved by
China's State Council in 1992, currently has 121 members, 63 of
which are brokerages, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The main metals traded at the exchange include copper,
aluminum, lead, zinc, tin and nickel. Combined metal futures
turnover were worth 1.8 trillion yuan for the past four years.
</P>
<P>
Zhou said that she believes there will be active futures
trading in nonferrous metals this year.  
</P>
