<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PICC Takes a Big Slice of Insurance market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The People's Insurance Company
of China (PICC), the country's leading insurer, has worked out an
ambitious plan to drive its annual premium income up to 150
billion yuan by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
According to the scheme, PICC's income from life insurance will
reach 71 billion yuan by that time, nine billion yuan more than
that from the property insurance.
</P>
<P>
However, over the past years, the company's life insurance
income has always lagged behind that generated from property
insurance.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese people will spend more money on life insurance, and
more insurance products will be generated, with more and more of
them becoming well-off," Wu Xiaoping, vice-president of PICC, said
at a press conference today.
</P>
<P>
"There is great potential to be tapped in China's insurance
market," he added.
</P>
<P>
The company's premium income will balloon by an average rate of
25.8 percent in the coming years, he said, adding that the company
will still hold most of the home insurance market in hand, even
though China promised to open its insurance sector to overseas
investors.
</P>
<P>
China now has three nationwide insurance companies, four
overseas offices in Shanghai and Guangzhou cities, and some other
regional and specialized companies.
</P>
<P>
And the number of insurance companies continues to grow.
</P>
<P>
But the PICC's will only be able to keep three-fourths of the
total domestic market shares, as the World Bank estimates that
China's booming insurance market will be around 2,000 billion yuan
by the year of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Before 1988, PICC was the sole state-owned insurance company in
China. The company was reorganized last July and shaped into a
commercial liability-limited enterprise that was to operate
according to market rules.
</P>
<P>
The company's premium income last year was about 63.4 billion
yuan in both domestic and overseas markets, up 25.2 percent from
1995. PICC Life, one of its three subsidiaries dealing in life
insurance, also set a new record in income growth last year.
</P>
<P>
PICC Life earned 21.2 billion yuan in premium income last year,
up 40 percent from 1995. The company now is focusing on China's
giant economic cities, targeting the more prosperous residents who
are likely to buy insurance policies.
</P>
<P>
PICC Property and PICC Reinsurance, the company's two other
subsidiaries, also have witnessed a stable increase of
income: PICC Property earned an income of 35 billion yuan last
year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, PICC chalked up a 35.1 billion-yuan-worth bill in
duty redemption in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0088 </DOCNO>
