<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highway Transport Maintains Momentum in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The country's highway system
remained a formidable opponent in the increasingly fierce market
competition throughout China's transportation sector in 1996.
</P>
<P>
While the number of train passengers dropped by 12.3 percent
last year, highway passenger transport volume rose by 9.5 percent
to 11.4 billion people. The passenger turnover reached 506 billion
people per km, a rise of 9.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Remaining the most important mode of transportation in China,
highways shipped 10 billion tons of goods last year, an increase
of 6.4 percent. The turnover was 500 billion ton/km, a rise of 6.5
percent, as compared with minor increases in train transport of
1.4 and 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Chinese highway officials attributed the growth to the unique
household-to-household system of highway transport as well as to
the rapid development in highway construction, especially the
building of high-grade roads and expressways, and the improvement
in rural roads.
</P>
<P>
According to a telephone conference held by the Ministry of
Communications here today, China completed 25,000 kilometers of
highways last year, bringing the total length to 1.18 million
kilometers. Of this amount, 17,800 kilometers are high-grade roads.
</P>
<P>
Last year was a milestone for the development of expressways in
China, with 1,117 kilometers of the roadways completed, bringing
the total to 3,258 kilometers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
