<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Lower Tariffs to 35 Percent in 3 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan is pursuing a
liberalized trade regime with lower tariffs which would be reduced
to 35 percent during the next three years, Commerce Minister
Muhammad Zubair said here today.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a lecture in a school, the minister said the present
level of tariffs is around 65 percent which is planned to be
lowered gradually in three years to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the country's exports grew by 7.9 percent
while imports recorded a growth of 13.9 percent during 1995-96
over the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Total exports were estimated at about 8.8 billion U.S. dollars
and imports 11.8 billion dollars during the last fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
He believed that at present the export sector is doing well and
the overall target of 10 billion dollars this year is expected to
be realized, provided the second half of the current fiscal year
sees better performance in this sector.  
</P>
