<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Railway Departments Go All Out Into Market Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- China's railway departments need
a strong market mechanism to meet fierce competition from road and
air travel, Railway Minister Han Zhubin said here today.
</P>
<P>
Han called for the establishment of special marketing
organizations and a high level team of staff at railway
stations.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking at an ongoing annual high-profile working
conference of central and local railway officials.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that trains carried a total ridership of
942 million last year, a 12.3 percent drop over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
According to Han, local railway bureaus will be given more
rights in terms of management in order to cater in a better way to
market operations.
</P>
<P>
Local units and railway enterprises will be entitled to rent
and contract slow trains, tourist trains, as well as dining,
container, and baggage cars in other trains. Railway sections can
also be rented out.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, local railway bureaus will be entitled to
readjust train schedules in line with concrete situations, and set
prices for some high-standard or express train services, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Railways will take measures to improve
services. A computerized ticketing network will be first used at
44 large stations, and other stations along four trunk lines --
Beijing-Guangzhou, Beijing-Shanghai, Beijing-Harbin, and
Lianyungang-Lanzhou, and will be spread to all other stations.
</P>
<P>
In order to be more competitive in terms of travel time, the
ministry plans to start 64 "arrive-in-a-night" return passenger
trains from April 1 of next year, when a new railway transport map
will be implemented.
</P>
<P>
And higher speeds will be introduced for trains that go as far
as 1,000 to 1,500 kilometers from the seven major railway hubs of
Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, Chengdu, Zhengzhou, Wuchang, and
Xi'an.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
