<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Air Macao performed much better
than expected, with a revenue of 650 million Patacas (about 82.28
million US dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Macao Daily News reported today that the airline took a
total of 5,700 flights, transporting 665,000 passengers last year.
As a result, the value of the airline's total assets went up to
500 million Patacas (about 63.29 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The better results reduced its expected loss of 120 million
Patacas (about 15.2 million US dollars) by half, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the airline plans to open a new air route to Qingdao
City in East China's Shandong province on March 23.
</P>
<P>
The airline will use an Airbus A-321 aircraft on the new route
with three scheduled flights a week.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Air Macao has regular flights to six destinations --
Beijing, Shanghai, Xiamen, Taipei, Kaohsiung and Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the airline plans to expand its air fleet from
four to six, adding another two Airbus A-321s in February and May
respectively. 
