<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin Meets Hong Kong Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
stressed here today that after July 1, 1997, the country will
never interfere in affairs to be handled by the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) according to the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with a delegation from the Chinese General Chamber of
Commerce of Hong Kong led by its Chairman Tsang Hin Chi, Jiang
said it has been a long-established state policy to implement the
principles of "one country, two systems," "the Hong Kong people
governing Hong Kong" and a high-degree of autonomy.
</P>
<P>
These principles not only benefit the six million Hong Kong
compatriots, but also work in the interests of the whole country,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that Hong Kong is a prosperous center of
international trade, finance, shipping and tourism, adding, "We
attach great importance to the unique role that Hong Kong is
playing."
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that the successful practice of the "one country,
two systems" concept cannot be realized without the unified
efforts of the Hong Kong people from all walks of life.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong compatriots have contributed to maintaining Hong
Kong's prosperity, stability and stable transition, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the process of attaining this goal, "we place our great hope
on the Hong Kong compatriots and wish them continuous
contributions to this end," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
"We have full confidence in Hong Kong's prosperity and
stability after July 1, 1997," he added.
</P>
<P>
Tsang said it is imperative to bring the chamber's fine
tradition of loving both the country and Hong Kong into full play,
and to more extensively unite the Hong Kong industrialists and
businessmen in order to contribute more to Hong Kong's smooth
return to the motherland and its long-term prosperity and
stability.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting were Wang Zhaoguo, vice-chairman of the
National Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference and minister of the United Front Work Department of the
Chinese Communist Party Central Committee, and Lu Ping, director
of the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office of the State Council.
