<HEADLINE> Wool Prices Likely to Increase in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Wool prices were likely to
increase in the second half of the season due to gradually
strengthening demand in Western Europe and steady demand in China,
Wool International (WI) said today.
</P>
<P>
In its January Insight newsletter, WI said that the eastern
market indicator was expected to average 620 Australian cents (496
US cents) a kilogram clean in the second half of the season, after
averaging 580 Australian cents (464 US cents) a kilogram in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
WI, the statutory body charged with selling Australia's wool
stockpile, had earlier forecast an eastern market indicator for
1996-97 of 620 Australian cents a kilogram.
</P>
<P>
"Prices for fleece wool in the 19-25 micron categories have
declined during the six months to December, with fine wool most
affected," WI said.
</P>
<P>
"However, prices for wool in the 26-31 micron categories were
generally steady or improved slightly over this period."
</P>
<P>
WI said that auction offerings for the first half of 1996-97
totaled 1.76 million bales, 20 percent higher than in the same
period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The pass-in rate at auction averaged 12 percent during the
first six months of the season, compared to 21 percent for the
same period last season, when prices were falling.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Kicks Off Mammoth Canal Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU SIMBEL, southern Egypt, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak today unveiled an ambitious project that
aims at adding Egypt's arable land by 30 percent and inhabiting
the vast parches south through digging a canal.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Zayed Canal, the so-called New Valley Canal, is just the
beginning of an integrated development project to divert people
from the crammed Old Nile Valley to new communities in the
Western Desert in two decades.
</P>
<P>
The irrigation potential is estimated at 2.2 million feddans
(924,000 hectares), equal to the capacity of the Aswan High Dam,
which had added 30 percent to the total cultivable area of Egypt
when its ten-year construction was completed in 1970.
</P>
<P>
Under the first stage, the 30-kilometer-long canal will be able
to irrigate at least half a million feddans (215,000 hectares)
with water diverted from the Aswan High Dam through the Toshki
Depression, where surplus water from the Lake Nasser has been
accumulating.
</P>
<P>
This will be accomplished by installing a pumping station, the
largest in the world, at the Toshki Depression to pump 30 million
cubic meters of water a day from a level of 150 meters to a level
of 200 meters into the new canal.
</P>
<P>
At the site of the envisaged canal, Mubarak will review the
blueprints for a number of other huge national projects, known as
"Egypt's 21st century project."
</P>
<P>
The integrated works will provide necessary infrastructure to
open the door for industrial, agricultural and tourism schemes on
the map of the New Delta.
</P>
<P>
During the inauguration ceremony, he will also unveil the
incentive packages planned by the government to encourage
investment in the areas, where 25 new heavy industry sites will be
set up.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri said earlier the
project was not merely for digging a canal, it aims at providing a
stable environment for building an agricultural community and
achieving sustainable and comprehensive development.
</P>
<P>
It will ease the imbalance of population distribution, enabling
58 percent of Egypt's land to be inhabited. At the moment, 99
percent of the population crams in the Nile Valley, which forms 4
percent of the land.
</P>
<P>
However, the costs are mammoth. Of the total 300 billion
Egyptian pounds (88 billion U.S. dollars), the government's
contributions, only 20 percent of the development costs, are
limited to providing the area with an infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the bills will be footed by international companies
and Egyptian and Arab private sectors, Xinhua learned.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak has assured the Egyptians that the giant project would
be carried out over four five-year plans in accordance with
Egypt's potential and resources.
</P>
<P>
"The first phase of the 30-kilometer-long canal will open the
door to investments in agriculture, land reclamation, industry,
mining, tourism and establishment of integrated urban communities
to absorb the expected population increase till the year 2017," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Ganzouri, who has recently inspected Toshki work site twice,
said the new projects, will incur investments to 61.3 million
feddans to cover mining, industrial and agricultural activities.
</P>
<P>
Comprehensive irrigational, geological and agricultural
research and lengthy plans have been conducted over the past
several years by specialized research centers.
</P>
<P>
Experts said to reclaim 500,000 feddans in the first phase
would need 5 billion cubic meters of water.
</P>
<P>
The first study of the New Valley development project was
conducted in 1960s, but it was reportedly delayed by preparations
for the 1967 Middle East War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
