<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saddam Pardons Iraqis with Illegal Connections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
has announced a pardon for Iraqi nationals who maintain illegal
connections with foreign forces, Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The phrase of Illegal connections with foreign forces is an
euphemism for spying.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued today by the presidency office said
that Saddam has decided to grant a full pardon for those who
were recruited by foreign intelligence agencies or maintained
unauthorized links with foreign parties.
</P>
<P>
Those covered by the pardon should surrender themselves to the
authorites concerned as from Thursday and until the end of the
holy month of Ramadan, the Islamic lunar year which falls on
January 11 this year, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
During the month of Ramadan, Muslims are forbidden to eat,
drink and hold parties from dawn to dusk.
</P>
<P>
INA quoted the presidency office as saying those who want to be
pardoned can report directly or indirectly to the authorities such
as the intelligence service, military intelligence, internal
security or any Baath party organizations.
</P>
<P>
Recently, two spy rings, one worked for the U.S. Central
Intelligence Agency (CIA), the other for Israeli Mossad, have been
uncovered in Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
