<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Fully Committed to IPR Protection after '97: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is fully committed
to the protection of intellectual property rights and will
continue to maintain a strong local IRP system to the highest
international standards after the handover, a ranking official
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meet-the-media session this afternoon, Stephen
Selby, director of Intellectual Property, said that much work had
been done by the Department of Intellectual Property in the past
year in updating and modernizing IP legislation.
</P>
<P>
The enactment of the Intellectual Property (World Trade
Organization Amendments) Ordinance 1996 in May last year was a
good example of Hong Kong's efforts in IPR protection, Selby said.
</P>
<P>
"Its enactment enables Hong Kong to meet its obligations under
the Agreement on Trade-Related Aspects of Intellectual Property
Rights (TRIPS) of the World Trade Organization (WTO), of which
Hong Kong is a founding member," he said.
</P>
<P>
Among the main features of the ordinance are new copyright
piracy offense provisions to help tackle masterminds of
cross-border piracy activities more effectively.
</P>
<P>
A patents bill which establishes an independent patent system
in Hong Kong for the protection of inventions in line with
international standards, was introduced here last June.
</P>
<P>
In addition, three bills, namely, Copyright Bill, Registered
Designs' Bill and Trademarks Bill, has been drafted.
</P>
<P>
On the other developments over the past year, closer
cooperation has been forged between the Intellectual Property
Department (IPD), the Customs and Excise Department and
TPR-related enforcement agencies in China to combat piracy.
</P>
<P>
On the progress of computerization, Selby said the department
established a computerized Trade Mark Registry System in the past
year and a Patents Computerization System would be implemented in
July this year.
</P>
<P>
Looking into 1997, Selby said the department is planning to
launch a major public education campaign at a cost of 1-2 million
HK dollars in conjunction with the private sector to promote
understanding and protection of intellectual property rights.
</P>
<P>
And if the current measures fail to prevent piracy from further
spreading, provision of laws would be proposed so that the IPD
could take actions as in the fight against drugs and prostitution,
Selby said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
