<HEADLINE> China Closing Factories In Pollution Elimination Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- China has closed 81.2 percent of
its small factories with serious pollution problems, according to
the latest official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the State Bureau of Environment Protection
show that the 57,430 factories that were closed include small
paper mills, leather processors, print and dye plants,
local-method coking plants.
</P>
<P>
The Bureau issued an order last year that required all of the
country's 15 types of small factories with serious pollution
problems to close.
</P>
<P>
Twelve provinces and municipalities that have closed their
polluting factories are now trying to find ways of preventing
the closed factories from resuming production, said an official
with the bureau.
</P>
<P>
South China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region and northwest
China's Shanxi Province have taken the lead in these actions, with
Guangxi having shut down 95.55 percent of the polluting factories,
according to statistics.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Gold Output Tops 120 Tons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- China's gold output reached
120.6 tons in 1996, up 11.8 percent from the previous year, having
overfulfilled the state production plan of 92-95 tons for the year.
</P>
<P>
Ai Dacheng, Deputy Director of the Gold Administration under
the Ministry of Metallurgical Industry (MMI), said at a press
conference here today that last year's gold output was 6.1 times
and 2.4 times that in 1978 and 1988, respectively.
</P>
<P>
China turned out 108 tons of gold in 1995, marking the first
time that the country's annual gold output exceeded 100 tons.
</P>
<P>
According to Jiao Zhi, Director of the Gold Administration,
China has a verified gold reserve of 4,500 tons, 1,100 tons of
which are gold mines associated with other non-ferrous metals.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the existing gold reserve is far from
enough to meet the fast-growing gold industry and the national
economy. Therefore, great efforts should be made to find more gold
mines.
</P>
<P>
Jiao said that the central government each year grants 400
million yuan of low-interest loans to support gold mine
prospecting.
</P>
<P>
Except for Shanghai, all Chinese provinces and autonomous
regions have gold resources.
</P>
<P>
According to Ai, 27 out of China's 31 gold-producing provinces,
municipalities, autonomous regions and cities with independent
planning had exceeded the production target of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Shandong, the leading gold producer in the country, turned out
29 tons of gold last year, up 13.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Regarding overseas investment in the country's gold industry,
Jiao Zhi said that so far, no overseas funds have entered into the
sector, but some overseas-funded projects are being negotiated.
</P>
<P>
China plans to turn out 150 tons of gold in the year 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
