<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian PM Vows to Build Competitive Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Deve
Gowda said today that his government is committed to building a
globally competitive industry in India.
</P>
<P>
"While foreign capital can play the role of a catalyst, the
main thrust has to be provided by our domestic industry," Gowda
said while inaugurating a three-day meeting sponsored by the
Federation of Indian Industries in Calcutta, West Bengal.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by British Prime Minister John Major
as well as business delegates from across the world.
</P>
<P>
Gowda said it is the government's policy to support Indian
entrepreneurs and enable them to grow.
</P>
<P>
"Upgrading of technological capability gives a nation true
inner strength," he noted.
</P>
<P>
As to the attraction of foreign investment, he said his
government has been targeting to get around 10 billion U.S.
dollars in foreign investment per year. Foreign investment will be
encouraged in core and infrastructure sectors, exports and
high-tech areas, he added.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said the Foreign Investment Promotion Board
has been thoroughly revamped to render decision-making quicker and
more transparent.
</P>
<P>
A foreign investment promotion council has been set up to
promote investment opportunities in India by giving advice to
stimulate inflow of foreign capital, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
