<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hebei to Use More Overseas Fund in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, January 9 (Xinhua) -- North China's Hebei
Province is expected to utilize 2.2 billion US dollars of overseas
funds in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government says that all trades, regions and
departments in Hebei will be open to overseas funds, except those
monopolized by the government.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 Hebei utilized two billion US dollars of overseas
funding, with 500 million US dollars in loans and 1.5 billion US
dollars in investment, up 27 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Cheng Weigao, secretary of the Provincial Committee of the
Chinese Communist Party, has stressed that all departments should
make efforts to attract overseas funding, including World Bank
loans, commercial loans and free economic aid. He said cooperation
can also be expanded into the fields of culture, sports, tourism
and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Hebei was one of the first 14 provinces to open to the outside
world. Cheng pointed out that, however, Hebei's extent of opening
was far from enough for such an economically large province.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 the province will continue to organize activities in
Hong Kong, Shijiazhuang and Xiamen to attract domestic and
overseas investments. The provincial government will also make
efforts to find diversified ways of attracting overseas funds.
</P>
<P>
The province will make public a list of projects costing over
ten million US dollars each for cooperation, and ensure the
projects receive a good service. About 100 state-owned enterprises
will utilize overseas funds to reform themselves in the next three
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
