<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arrested S. Leone Military Officers Questioned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The five military officers of
the Sierra Leone army arrested on Sunday were questioned by a
joint army and police team on Monday, sources here disclosed
today.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, the five officers are LT Colonel
Tom Nyuma, Major Francis Kamara and Captain Paul Thomas and
retired Lieutenants Kindama Kargbo and Jeff Kallon. Another
officer, Colonel Kes Boya was questioned and allowed to go, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The three serving officers were then put under arrest which
they are under until now.
</P>
<P>
The two retired lieutenants are still detained by police in
Freetown together with a Sierra Leonean lawyer, Andrew Kaikai who
practices in london, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
No official explanation for the men's arrest have been made
but police investigators say the men ''would have to explain how
they spent the whole Sunday of January 5 and their movements and
actions along a prominent beach in the capital.''
</P>
<P>
Family sources Thursday confirmed that the residence of
Captain Paul Thomas, Colonel Nyuma and Major Kamara were
''thoroughly searched by military police three times but nothing
of relevance in terms of arms and ammunition or documents were
found.''
</P>
<P>
''Nyuma was on the verge of returning back to Zimbabwe to
resume his military studies,'' one of his relatives said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
