<HEADLINE> New Cable Network Starts to Link Up in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The Asia Pacific Cable
Network, a 11,840-kilometer submarine telecommunication cable
network, started to link up nine countries and regions today.
</P>
<P>
Employing the latest optical amplifier technology, the
580-million-U.S.-dollar project is jointly invested by 51
telecommunications entities worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The project was initiated by 10 telecommunications carriers
including Cellular Communication Network of Malaysia,
Communication Authority of Thailand, Hongkong Telecom, Indosat of
Indonesia, Kokusai Denshin Denwa Co. Ltd. of Japan and Singapore
Telecommunications Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Alistair Grieve, deputy chief executive of Hongkong Telecom,
said, "Hongkong Telecom is pleased to take part in this major step
toward better connection among Asian countries and regions."
</P>
<P>
He said using the most advanced optical amplification method in
transmission signals, the network provides a reliable network for
Hong Kong, Indonesia, Japan, South Korea, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Taiwan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
