<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unified Seed Supply Play Big Role in Shandong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The unified supply of improved
seed strains has proved to be an important factor in the good
harvest of farm produce in east China's Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
So far, over 80 percent of seeds planted in Shandong were
provided by local seed companies. Nearly 95 percent of land for
grain, cotton and vegetable production was sown with improved
seeds.
</P>
<P>
Experiments have shown that replacing a single seed generation
would raise the output by at least 10 percent. The practice helps
to prevent seed degeneration and a decline in production,
according to a local agricultural official.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, Shandong has spent 54 million yuan to
research, develop and popularize improved seed strains. It has
built 20 seed production bases which offer 1.5 billion kg of
improved seed in five categories.
</P>
<P>
Seed improvement will continue to be a key element in achieving
the goal of raising the annual grain output to 45 billion kg by
the year 2000, set by the provincial government, the official said.
</P>
<P>
In the coming four years, the province plans to develop 50
high-yielding seed strains, which are expected to raise the unit
grain output by 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
The role played by agro-science in agricultural production will
rise to 50 percent by the end of this century, the official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
