<HEADLINE> Former Indian PM Granted Bail in Bribery Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Former Indian prime minister
P.V. Narasimha Rao was granted regular bail today by a Delhi court
in a bribery case, Press Trust of India said.
</P>
<P>
The designated judge of the Central Bureau of Investigation,
Ajit Bharihoke, granted bail to Rao and other eight accused on
their furnishing bail bonds of 50,000 rupees (about 1,430 US
dollars) and a surety of like amount each.
</P>
<P>
Rao has been accused of paying 35 million rupees (about one
million dollars) to four members of parliament from a small party
to buy their support in a crucial vote of confidence in his
government in July 1993. 
</P>
