<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Restates Opposition to NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov today reaffirmed Moscow's opposition to the planned
eastward expansion of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO), demanding a voice in the alliance's decision-making
concerning Russia's "vital interests."
</P>
<P>
Outlining Russia's foreign policy in 1997, Primakov said that
Moscow would welcome NATO's offer of a new relationship between
them if the Western military alliance proves its willingness to
take into account Russia's concerns.
</P>
<P>
He said the major indicator of NATO's "seriousness of
intentions" is whether it agrees adjustments to the Treaty on
Conventional Forces in Europe (CFE), which sets limits of Soviet
weapons in Europe, and whether it consults with Russia on
important issues.
</P>
<P>
"If we manage to reach agreement on the modernization of
CFE ... and to create a mechanism for making joint decisions with
NATO concerning Russia's vital interests and other issues, we will
sign the appropriate document (on a special relationship),"
Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with the Itar-Tass news agency at the
end of his first year in office, the minister called on NATO to
step up efforts to build a special relationship with Moscow, which
NATO proposed in a December meeting.
</P>
<P>
"Officially the talks on this issue (working out a document on
special relations) have not started yet," he said. "They are steps
in the right direction, but they are partial and insufficient."
</P>
<P>
Russia considered NATO's plan to take in eastern and central
European countries, which possibly means nuclear deployment on
Russia's border, a serious threat to its security.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that NATO is likely to invite some of the 11
applicants for joining the bloc to participate the NATO summit in
June. Among the favorite candidates are Poland, Hungary and the
Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Moscow has no right to veto NATO's expansion,
Primakov said that "no one, including NATO members, can veto our
right to defend our national interests."
</P>
<P>
He warned that NATO's enlargement will lead to "new divisions
in Europe."
</P>
<P>
Primakov said Russia will continue to seek favorable external
conditions for democratization and economic reform and to remain
one of the influential centers in the multi-polarized world.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Russia's foreign diplomacy in 1996, he said
Russia's effort to reverse its "excessive inclination" towards the
West and to cement ties with Asian neighbors in the past year had
proved successful.
</P>
<P>
Having tremendous interests in Asia, Russia "purposefully and
actively developed political dialog and economic ties with leading
Asian countries," including China, India and Japan, Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
"Extraordinary progress has been made in Russia's relations
with China," he said, noting that in last year the border issue
overshadowing bilateral relations had been solved for the first
time in history.
</P>
<P>
"We will complete border surveying in 1997," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, he said Russia did not want to revive the ideological
union between the two giants in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
"The Russians and the Chinese agreed that an equal and trustful
partnership aimed at strategic cooperation in the 21st century
would better serve both countries' interests," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
