<HEADLINE> Overseas Funds Pouring into Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Liaoning Province, northeast
China, made use of 2.1 billion U.S. dollars of overseas funds last
year, a rise of 10 percent over 1995.
</P>
<P>
It included 1.7 billion U.S. dollars of foreign direct
investments, up 18.7 over the 1995 figure, according to Gao
Guozhu, deputy governor of the province.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning Province is China's oldest industrial base and has
1,400 large and medium-sized state-owned enterprises, accounting
for one tenth of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
The province has so far approved the establishment of 14,600
overseas-funded enterprises, involving an agreed use of 20.3
billion U.S. dollars of overseas funds.
</P>
<P>
Approval was given last year for 1,700 enterprises, involving a
promised use of four billion U.S. dollars in overseas funds.
</P>
<P>
A total of 6,100 overseas-backed enterprises in Liaoning
province have started operations. These enterprises have generated
50 billion yuan (six billion U.S. dollars) of output value last
year, contributing 1.9 billion yuan in taxes to local finances,
and earning 2.6 billion U.S. dollars from exports in 1996, all
showing marked rises over the same period of the previous year.
</P>
</TEXT>
