<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine "Comfort Women" Picket Japanese Embassy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- A group of former Philippine
"comfort women," or sex slaves of Japanese soldiers during World
War II, held a protest rally in front of the Japanese Embassy here
today, demanding official compensation and apologies from the
Japanese government.
</P>
<P>
Waving banners and flags and singing songs, about 60 aged women
picketed the Japanese Embassy for about one hour this afternoon.
One of them collapsed on the scene because of sunstroke.
</P>
<P>
They demanded that the Japanese parliament adopt a draft
compensation law, which will provide for "individual state
compensation and official apologies" for the "comfort women"
survivors.
</P>
<P>
They reiterated their determination not to accept compensation
provided by the private Japanese group Asian Women's Fund (AWF)
and called on the Japanese government to act now because "they are
dying."
</P>
<P>
Police did not intervene in the brief rally, which was jointly
organized by two non-governmental groups, Lila Pilipina and Asian
Women's Human Rights Council.
</P>
<P>
Nelia Sancho, chairwoman of Lila Pilipina, told Xinhua that
today's rally is just the start of a series of actions her group
will organize to keep up pressure on the Japanese government.
</P>
<P>
"After we strove for four years, the AWF agreed to come here
next week for fact-finding. But there is still no official
response from the Japanese government," Sancho said.
</P>
<P>
She said five more rallies will be held in front of the
Japanese Embassy by the end of March. The next rally will take
place on January 16.
</P>
<P>
Maloo Sabado, a member of Asian Women's Human Rights Council,
said there were a total of 169 documented Philippine comfort women
during the World War II, but the actual number was much higher.
</P>
<P>
According to Sabado, there are more than 100 comfort women
still alive in the country.
</P>
<P>
During World War II, many women in the Korean Peninsula, China,
the Philippines and some other Asian countries were forced by the
Japanese military to act as "comfort women."
</P>
<P>
After the war, the Japanese government had denied this atrocity
for decades until 1996, but it refused to give individual state
compensation and make official apologies to former comfort women.
A so-called Asian Women's Fund was later created to pay
compensation to former comfort women.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
