<HEADLINE> Industrial Production in Chinese Island Province Keeps Growing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, January 9 (Xinhua) -- China's southernmost province of
Hainan is expected to have 16 percent industrial growth figure for
1996 because of a modernization drive the island began to boost
its fledgling industries.
</P>
<P>
The province's industrial fixed assets have grown 40 percent
annually since 1988, when the island was separated from Guangdong
Province and became a province itself.
</P>
<P>
The province's industrial output value exceeded 14 billion yuan
(1.68 billion US dollars) last year, almost five times that of the
late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Because of provincial government preferential policies, the
chemical, automotive, motorcycle, and wool spinning sectors have
become the province's fastest-growing money-makers.
</P>
<P>
In the next five years, the province plans to develop the
country's largest production base for carbamide, a widely-used
chemical fertilizer in China's rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The province will also provide petrochemicals for the rest of
China, with two plants producing ethylene and methanol and a
high-capacity oil refinery to be completed in 1998. The refinery
will provide six million tons of oil yearly.
</P>
<P>
Officials say that in the coming five years the province will
spend some 56 billion yuan (6.74 billion US dollars) on a number
of industrial projects, and increase its industrial output value
by more than 40 billion yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
