<HEADLINE> Ancient Commercial Town Described in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Archaeologists in east China's
Jiangxi province have found an ancient architectural complex in
the province. They describe it was a commercial town built during
the early and late periods of the Qing dynasty (1644-1911).
</P>
<P>
Discovered in Egret (Bailu) Village in the Ganxian county, the
streets and buildings remain intact, and are seen as a rare museum
for the study of the ancient commercial activities.
</P>
<P>
Located at the foot of a mountain and besides a limpid stream,
the newly-excavated town, in a shape of crescent moon, is one
km long and 0.5 km. wide.
</P>
<P>
Among more than 50 buildings in the town, each has a bright and
spacious hall circled by carved banisters with colorful paintings,
said Zhang Sijie, curator of the county museum.
</P>
<P>
He added that the buildings all have quite different styles of
decorations, such as sculptures of lions, fish and phoenix, as
well as the kylin, a legendary animal.
</P>
<P>
Experts noted that the complex would benefit the study of
archaeology, classic architecture and art, as well as the
development of villages and towns.
</P>
<P>
The town, after renovation and preservation and protection
work, is also expected to be turned into a new sightseeing spot,
according to experts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
