<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 08:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Plans to Impose Corporate Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait is considering to
introduce corporate taxes by the year of 2000 as part of its
plans to rationalize the state's finances, according to Kuwaiti
financial sources.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Planning Minister Ali Al-Zumai while explaining a
financial program of action said Wednesday that Kuwaiti
government is considering "taxes on profits of companies and
institutions."
</P>
<P>
He said the initiative would be among a series of measures
aimed at streamlining state finances to prevent the state budget
deficit from growing again in the future.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti budget deficit which hugely rose after the Gulf War
was forecast at more than five billion US dollars for 1995-96
fiscal year, but the actual figure has been slashed to a little
more than two billion U.S. dollars due to higher oil prices
since last June.
</P>
<P>
Oil earnings from production of some two million barrels a
day currently account for about 85 percent of the state revenues
of the small oil-dependent economy.
</P>
<P>
The minister said Kuwaiti five-year plan of 1996-2000 was
aimed at helping the country diversify its financial resources
and increasingly shed the oil dependency.
</P>
<P>
He said customs fees on imported goods and government public
administration services could be raised as new measures to
increase non-oil financial resources.
</P>
<P>
At present, only foreign firms pay taxes in Kuwait, and
Kuwaiti government recently said these taxes would be cut to 30
percent from the current 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
On the state expenditure, Zumai did not rule out a government
reduction of subsidies on state-run services. mainly the
electricity and telecommunication services which together
account for 40 percent of the government expenditure.
</P>
<P>
"The government only needs to rationalize expenditure in
these two sectors," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, he said Kuwait has no plans to impose income tax or
any other form of taxes on individuals before the year of 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
