<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 350 Cars Stolen In Australia Each Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Australian cars are stolen at
the rate of 350 a day, worse than the level of vehicle theft in
the United States, Canada and Germany.
</P>
<P>
In preliminary figures from a paper to be issued later this
month, Director of the Australian Institute of Criminology Adam
Graycar said the Australian motor vehicle theft trade was a
billion-dollar business.
</P>
<P>
"Data shows the figure is around 643 million Australian dollars
(514.4 million U.S. dollars) for the 1995-96 financial year. The
figure did not include indirect costs such as police and court
expenditure, loss of earnings and higher insurance premiums,"
Graycar said.
</P>
<P>
Young males were still the major perpetrators, and most of
these crimes were by amateurs for joy riding.
</P>
<P>
Official figures showed the number of cars, station wagons and
four-wheel drives has doubled since 1965 in the country, with 84
percent of households now having at least one vehicle. More than
70 percent of Australians use a car each day, compared with 33
percent who walk, 9 percent who take public transport and two
percent who ride a bike (some people use more than one transport
each day).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
