<HEADLINE> Soeharto, Hashimoto Will Not Touch Contentious Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
and Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, who arrived here
today for a three-day visit, are unlikely to raise contentious
issues in their bilateral talks, officials from the Indonesian
Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders are expected to discuss efforts to maintain and
cement the two countries' bilateral relations rather than
controversial issues, such as Indonesia's national car policy and
human rights in East Timor, said the officials.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto's program on the first day of his first official
visit to Indonesia is primarily ceremonial. This includes a
courtesy call on Soeharto and Vice President Try Sutrisno and a
state banquet to be hosted by Soeharto at the state palace in the
evening.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders are scheduled to hold talks Friday and are
expected to cover domestic, regional and global issues.
</P>
<P>
This is the third leg of Hashimoto's eight-day tour of five
Southeast Asian countries, namely, Brunei, Malaysia, Indonesia,
Vietnam and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Japan is Indonesia's leading trading partner and biggest source
of aid and investment.
</P>
<P>
Japanese investment in Indonesia nearly doubled to about 7
billion U.S. dollars in 1996 from 3.8 billion dollars in the
previous year and 53 percent of Japan's vital imports of raw
materials pass through Indonesia's sea lines.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is also Japan's third largest foreign source of oil
and natural gas.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto will leave for Vietnam Saturday before proceeding to
Singapore.  
</P>
</TEXT>
