<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some Beijing Kindergartens Turned into Old Folks Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Several kindergartens in
Beijing's urban areas have been restyled into an old folks home,
and experts here believe that such merging will become a trend in
large Chinese cities in the future.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, the four kindergartens on Yongwai Street
in the capital's Chongwen District annually enrolled some 500
children. But in 1996, they only registered a total of 79
youngsters.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, people over the age of 60 accounted
for 18.3 percent of the street's total population of 80,000. Many
are chronically ill, and do not have family members available to
help with health care.
</P>
<P>
To tackle both problems, residents on Yongwai Street raised
money and transformed three of the kindergartens into a residence
for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
The new old folks home, which can accommodate 50 people, has
bedrooms, gym facilities, color TVs, sofas and games.
</P>
<P>
The work staff are all women who have been laid-off, who have
prior experience in taking care of the elderly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
