<HEADLINE> Rising Tax Revenues from Foreign-Funded Enterprises in Yantai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANTAI, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The steady inflow of overseas
investment in Yantai, a coastal city in east China's Shandong
Province, helped the city lead the province last year to take in
390 million yuan in tax revenues from local foreign-funded
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Also in 1996, Yantai ranked first among the provincial big
cities in its nearly 49 percent growth in tax revenues, 127
million yuan more than in the previous year,
</P>
<P>
Among the total amount, nearly 96 million yuan was retrieved
in the Yantai Development Zone, more than double the 1995 figure.
</P>
<P>
The inflow of overseas funds into Yantai began in 1985, when
the city had only eight foreign-financed enterprises, collecting
only 130,000 yuan of taxes from them.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992 a large amount of overseas investors have rushed
into the city, bringing the number of foreign-funded enterprises
to 3,735.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, over 500 companies were added in 1996, including
more than 10 with investment surpassing 10 million US dollars each.
</P>
<P>
The increased overseas funds in the city is a result of
improvement of the local investment environment.
</P>
<P>
Yantai, which is among the first group of the nation's coastal
cities to open to the outside world, has become one of China's
leading cities by hitting 68 billion yuan in GDP in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
