<HEADLINE> Australian Opposition Calls for National Population </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The Australian Opposition today
called the coalition government to develop a national population
policy and stated they could contribute to building a responsible
bipartisan population policy.
</P>
<P>
Opposition immigration spokesman Duncan Kerr said in a
statement that on current birth rates and excluding net migration,
Australia population would begin to decline around the year 2036
and continue to fall.
</P>
<P>
He said such a trend, if not checked, would lead to a grim
outlook for jobs and general prosperity.
</P>
<P>
According to an official report issued earlier, the country's
population at the end of 1995 was 18.1 million, and there was a
clear long-term trend declining from current rates of between 1.0
and 1.3 percent annually to between 0.2 to 0.5 percent by 2051.
</P>
<P>
If there was no net gain from overseas migration, the rate of
growth would be even slower. In this case the projected population
could peak at around 20.7 million in the year 2033 and decline to
20.1 million by 2051, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The opposition was not advocating a particular population
target, but urged the government to abandon its current emphasis
on the short-term and not to allow itself to be pushed into a
corner by "ill-informed and narrow-minded people", Kerr alleged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
