<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanians Jailed in Kuwait Visited by Family </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Jordanians jailed in
Kuwaiti prisons since the Gulf War in 1991 met their relatives on
January 6-8, a statement issued by the Kuwaiti-based
International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) said today.
</P>
<P>
The statement said "34 Jordanian citizens imprisoned in Kuwait
after the Gulf War met their family members between January 6 and
8 through an ICRC-organized humanitarian operation."
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Interior Ministry sources said the visit, the third
time by the relatives of the prisoners, was made possible through
intensive cooperation and coordination between the two countries'
ministries of interior and foreign affairs and was financed by
the ICRC.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti state security court sentenced dozens of Jordanians,
Palestinians and others to long imprisonment on charges of
assisting Iraqi troops during Iraq's seven-month occupation of
Kuwait in the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Strained relations between the two countries caused by
Jordan's support for Iraq during the Gulf War have shown signs of
ease since 1996 as contacts and exchange of letters were made
between their leaders.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Sheikh
Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah has voiced hope that 1997 would see
reconciliation of relations between Kuwait and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti sources said that the new visit is also an
evidence that Kuwait is keen in consolidating humanitarian
treatment with prisoners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drought Hits Tanzania's Arusha Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Over 61 out of the 71
man-made dams in Arusha Region, northern Tanzania, have dried up
for lack of rains between last October and January this year.
</P>
<P>
The Arusha Regional Commissioner, Daniel Njoolay, said on
Wednesday that Monduli District was most seriously hit.
</P>
<P>
He explained that usually the region received rains between
October and January, but this time, a
number of districts received little rain or no rain at all.
</P>
<P>
Njoolay gave an example of Arkatan village in Monduli District
as a drought-hit area where villagers were compelled to buy a
20-litre tin of water for domestic use at the price of 300
Tanzania Shillings (about 0.5 U.S. Dollar).
</P>
<P>
He cited Babat District as the second drought-hit area where
all dams have dried up. Other districts with more or less similar
problems include Mbulu, Karatu, Ngorongoro and Arumeru in
northern Tanzania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
