<HEADLINE> Wireless Telecom Development in Northwest Chinese Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Landlocked Shaanxi Province in
northwestern China is putting wireless telecommunications at the
top of its list of information projects, and will develop an
advanced wireless communications network by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
According to Beijing's "China Electronics News," the province
will have two expansion projects for its satellite telecom network
by the year 2000, and double 1995's business figure.
</P>
<P>
The three wireless telecom channels now in use will be expanded
to eight, and the business volume will increase by seven times by
2000.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an, the provincial capital, will become a hub for China's
longest SDH (synchronous digital hierarchy) digital microwave
trunk, which connects the provincial capitals Wuhan and Lanzhou.
The trunk will form a high-speed information corridor east and
west together with the Jinan-Taiyuan-Chengdu microwave line, which
also crosses Xi'an.
</P>
<P>
The paper says that a sophisticated communications network will
take shape in Shaanxi by the end of 1997, combining such new
technology as optical fiber, satellite, microwave, and emergency
telecommunication technology into a unified province-wide web.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
