<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some 800 Relics Salvaged from Famous Sunken Warship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, January 9 (Xinhua) -- More than 800 relics including
shells, rifles, stationery, and private seals have been salvaged
from a famous warship sunk in the Yangtze River by Japanese
military aircraft 58 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Among the more valuable items, according to experts, is a
copper plate bearing the inscription "Zhungshan Cruiser," used for
identification of the ship, which was named after Dr. Sun Yat-sen
(Zhungshan), the forerunner of the Chinese democratic revolution.
</P>
<P>
Inscriptions such as "Do not fear death and do not covet money"
were found on the rifles.
</P>
<P>
The relics were discovered when divers were clearing away sand
and mud in the cruiser to assist the salvage work. More than 1,100
work hours were spent to remove over 1,000 tons of sand and mud in
the ship.
</P>
<P>
The divers are now trying to place 20 steel cables under the
sunken cruiser to form a steel net so that the shop can be lifted
out of the water intact.
</P>
<P>
The salvage project, drawing an investment of some 100 million
yuan, began on November 12.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
