<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Link With Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese General Posts
Department has installed Internet Vietnam, which will be directly
linked up with international Internet, local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Internet project has been carried out in two phases. the
first phase was the establishment of two gateways in Hanoi and Ho
Chi Minh city, and the upgrading of the Hanoi gateway which will
become the country's gateway.
</P>
<P>
The second phase, to be completed within 1997, will see the
expansion of Internet activities across the whole country, and an
increase in equipment capacity as well as transmission speeds
inside and outside the country.
</P>
<P>
At present, two gateways in Hanoi and Ho Chi Minh city and a
link with the international Internet through Australia in Ho Chi
Minh city are in operation.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, the National Center for Natural Science and
Technology, the Science Information and the Center for Science and
Technology in Ho Chi Minh city have used the Internet for
information exchange. However, these nets are not online when
connect with the international Internet.
</P>
<P>
Gradually these nets will be unified into Internet Vietnam
which will supply Internet services throughout the country. It is
expected that Internet Vietnam will be officially registered
within the international Internet in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Sino-Us Negotiations on Bilateral Textile Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Delegations from China and the
United States have decided to hold a fourth round of negotiations
on a new bilateral textile agreement in Beijing, starting January
27.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came from a spokesman for the Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (Moftec) in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
During the previous round of negotiations, held in Washington
from December 19 to 21, the U.S. side indicated that U.S. Customs
is re-examining quota reduction cases and the results would be
passed on to the Chinese side during the next round of
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Because of this, the spokesman said, the deadline set by Moftec
and the General Administration of Customs, wherein China will
implement a temporary suspension of imports of some US products,
has been postponed to the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
The two Chinese government departments provided a month-long
grace period for the ban on some US imports that was to start on
December 10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
