<HEADLINE> Increased Overseas Funds for Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Sichuan
Province approved the establishment of 425 overseas-backed
enterprises in 1996, with the contracts involving 570 million
U.S. dollars of overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
According to local officials, 24 of the projects each required
investment of more than 10 million U.S. dollars, claiming about 50
percent of the agreed use of overseas investment in the past year.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, overseas-backed businesses generated 10
billion yuan (8.3 billion U.S. dollars) in output value last year,
and earned 11 billion yuan in total sales and 220 million
U.S. dollars from exports.
</P>
<P>
Foreign-backed firms have also created jobs for 300,000 people
in the province.
</P>
<P>
The officials added that most of the foreign fund inflow was
used in production-oriented projects, and foreign investment in
machinery, transportation, railway construction, construction of
infrastructure in urban and rural areas and in other industries is
also increasing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
