<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Involvement in Baghdad Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Foreign Ministry
Wednesday night rejected the Iraqi allegation that Iran was
involved in a blast in the Iraqi capital Baghdad, the official
news agency IRNA reported today.
</P>
<P>
IRNA quoted a spokesman of the ministry as saying "such
baseless charges are merely aimed at distracting the public
opinion from Iraq's internal problems."
</P>
<P>
Baghdad blamed Iran for a bombing near the headquarters of the
anti-government organization of Iran -- People's Mujahedeen
Organization (PMO) -- in central Baghdad Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
But the Iranian Foreign Ministry's spokesman said that
linking internal problems and impotencies to foreign elements was
an "old useless and tired propaganda attempt."
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Iranian Law Enforcement Forces killed two
PMO members and arrested two others in recent clashes in western
Iranian border region.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, PMO staged a series of bombing around the country
during the fourth parliamentary elections. Tehran government
reacted by staging an air raid on PMO base inside the Iraqi
territory.
</P>
<P>
Massoud Rajavi is PMO's leader who lives in Iraq at the
moment. There are reportedly about 20,000 anti-government forces
in Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
