<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Megawati-led PDI Not Allowed to Campaign for Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government will
not allow Megawati Soeharnopuri's faction in the Indonesian
Democratic Party (PDI) to stage election campaigns on its own
behalf, Home Affairs Ministry Spokesman Hsa. Yussac said.
</P>
<P>
"The government's stand has since the beginning been clear that
only the PDI under the party leadership elected at the Medan
Congress will be permitted to organize election campaign," he said
Wednesday in Yogyakarta, Central Java, reports reaching here today
said.
</P>
<P>
A government-backed PDI congress was held in Medan, North
Sumatra, last June. At the congress, Soerjadi, a veteran party
member, was elected party chairman to replace Megawati who gains
strong support from most of the party members.
</P>
<P>
Megawati, however, has refused to accept the congress's outcome
claiming that the congress had been held in violation of party
rules.
</P>
<P>
Yussac said any request from Megawati's camp to be permitted to
hold an election campaign would be rejected.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian people are expected to hold a general election
on May 29 this year.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the internal frictions in the PDI, Yussac said the
government was quite aware of them. "The government knows there
are still problems within the PDI but they are the party's
internal affairs and the government hopes the conflicting sides
will eventually reunite," he said.
</P>
<P>
The three officially-recognized parties, the ruling Golkar,
PDI and the United Development Party (PPP), will compete in the
forthcoming elections for 425 seats in the parliament.
Seventy-five other seats are to be filled by members of the
Indonesian Armed Forces appointed by the president. The armed
forces do not cast votes in the polling.
</P>
<P>
Golkar has won each of the five general elections held in the
country since 1971. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
