<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archeologists Find 890-year-old Buddist Grottoes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Seven ancient grottoes and a
number of Buddist statues have been found in northwest China's
Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region along the route of the famous Silk
Road.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists said that the grottoes were created on a rock
hill 890 years ago in the Song Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
The biggest cave is 6.3 meters wide and 10 meters long, and
contains more than 10 Buddist niches. However the Buddist statues
that would have originally been placed in them are missing.
</P>
<P>
There was a 30-centimeter-high Buddist statue above the cave,
which was surrounded by 42 smaller statues.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists have found a number of statues in another two of
the caves, but the rest were empty.
</P>
<P>
The grottoes, though not as grand and famous as those at
Yungang and Longmen, are still significant for the study of
ancient politics and culture, as well as the myths of the famous
Silk Road, a trade route linking China with central Asia,
archeologists said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
