<HEADLINE> Industrial Firms Go in for Farming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENZHOU, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The Lianfa Industrial
Corporation in Central China's Henan province has signed a
contract to manage 6,600 hectares of grain farmland in the next
ten years.
</P>
<P>
It is another big step by the company towards farmland
activity, following breeding of smaller animals.
</P>
<P>
By entering the agricultural sector, Lianfa has developed in
three years into a large firm with assets of 100 million yuan,
from its initial one million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The firm is now listed seventh in the province's 50 top
agricultural companies.
</P>
<P>
Lianfa is not the only example of industrial and commercial
firms to launch themselves into farmland industries in Henan, a
major grain producer in the country.
</P>
<P>
More firms than ever are casting their eyes on farming
businesses as a means of seeking high returns.
</P>
<P>
The province has also given full support to firms moving into
farming. It plans to provide 100 million yuan in loans to 50 firms
engaged in farming and agricultural products processing this year.
</P>
<P>
The local government noted that the industrial firms will bring
with them more funds, advanced techniques and management expertise
to farming, helping to promote the rapid development of
agriculture. In return, they will enjoy high profits from
large-scale farming production.
</P>
<P>
Lianfa has invested more than two million yuan in
buying advanced large agricultural machinery and building water
conservancy projects.
</P>
<P>
With the efforts, the company's farmland is likely to yield
more grain, and this is expected to provide the firm with a
investment return as high as 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition to developing large-scale farm production, some
firms have put their money into barren mountains and wasteland.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some agricultural products processing firms
extending their processing capacity, have begun to stablize their
supply of raw materials by setting up their own raw material
bases. Farmland has become the "first workshop" of the companies.
</P>
<P>
Luoyang Chundu Group, with its brand product of "Chundu"
sausage, has launched an animal husbandry project. According to
the plan the suburb areas of Luoyang city will provide the group
with more than five million pigs a year by 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
