<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Army repulses Tamil Rebels Attack In North </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan government troops
today successfully repulsed a heavy attack by the Tamil rebels in
the Northern province of the island country, Defense Ministry
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that early this morning at 04:00, the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) rebels launched a heavy
attack on task force 2 area at Elephant Pass and Paranthan Army
camps.
</P>
<P>
The raid was successfully repulsed by the government troops,
the sources said, adding that the LTTE is withdrawing its cadres
now, by boat and land towards the East.
</P>
<P>
According to unconfirmed reports, over 1,000 rebel cadres had
besieged the Paranthan Camp and they had broken through the
forward defense lines of the camp. The rebels were later driven
out of the camp perimeter.
</P>
<P>
Paranthan Camp is one of several small camps in the narrow
stretch of territory now held by the government troops stretching
from the major Elephant Pass base, the gateway to Jaffna Peninsula
which is heavily protected by the government troops.
</P>
<P>
During the past year, the LTTE rebels who have been fighting
for a separate Tamil state since 1983, suffered severe reversals
with their heartland Jaffna Peninsula recaptured by government
troops and they themselves forced to retreat into Jungle hideouts
in the north and east. 
</P>
</TEXT>
