<HEADLINE> Turkey Warns Against Arms Build-Up in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has warned against an arms
build-up by Greek Cypriots on the Mediterranean island, saying
that it would lead to a disaster, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Daily News, in a story carried today, voiced
its opposition to military confrontation in the island and termed
surface-to-air missiles to be purchased from Russia as "suicide
weapons."
</P>
<P>
Daily New quoted a military source, who asked not to be named,
as saying that in event of an all-out military confrontation, the
S-300 anti-aircraft missiles, which Greek Cypriots are to buy from
Russia, would be disastrous for the small Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
The missiles, however, can not change the military balance
on the divided island, and the Turkish troops still have the
power to defend the north part of Cyprus, the source said.
</P>
<P>
Tension has been rapidly increasing in Cyprus after Greek
Cypriots singed a contract with Russia Saturday to buy the
offensive surface-to-air missiles.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Turkey government claimed that it would take
necessary actions if the situation in Cyprus continued to
deteriorate, reiterating that Turkish troops were strong enough to
protect Turkish Cypriots living in northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman Nicolas Burns Monday criticized
Greek Cypriots for purchasing the missiles from Russia, saying it
would only serve to complicate the efforts aimed to achieve a
lasting peace in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
But Greek Cypriots rejected the criticism of the
U.S. government and stressed its purchase of missiles from
Russian was completely for defense purpose.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into two parts since 1974 when the
Turkish troops landed on the island and took control of the
northern part following an abortive coup by Greek Cypriots seeking
union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
