<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Football Hits Saves Student's Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 9 (Xinhua) -- A freak football accident has
saved the life of a Chinese teenager in south China's Guangdong
Province.
</P>
<P>
High school student Wu Xinhui was rushed to hospital in severe
pain after a football struck him in the stomach.
</P>
<P>
When doctors operated on the 17 year old, they discovered two
life-threatening tumors - both fist sized - on his liver.
</P>
<P>
Surgeons have now removed the tumors and Wu is out out of
hospital and is in good health after intensive medical care in
south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Wu Xinhui, a high school student from Guandong's Shixin county,
was playing in a football game last April when suddenly the
football hit him in the stomach.
</P>
<P>
Wu fainted with the pain, and when he was rushed to a nearby
hospital, where doctors gave him a medical check by cutting open
his stomach. They found there two fist-sized tumors on his liver,
and they were broken and bleeding after the accident.
</P>
<P>
Wu was unaware that he had the liver tumors. As the tumors were
too large, and located right in the center of the liver, the
doctors decided not to risk operating on them. Instead they
carried out some repair work and tried to stop the bleeding.
</P>
<P>
Later Wu had another operation, but it was not successful.
</P>
<P>
Several weeks ago Wu turned to the South Hospital, and doctors
there found the tumors had caused pathological changes to his
liver, and if they could not be removed in time it would endanger
Wu's life.
</P>
<P>
After careful preparation, doctors successfully cut off the
tumors and the post-operative medical care helped Wu resume his
good health within two weeks. Now Wu is healthy again.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
