<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solar Breakthrough Can End Highway Ice Age Misery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Treacherous ice-covered highways
could become a thing of the past following the invention in China
of a highway material that stores solar heat.
</P>
<P>
Its use will melt snow, avoiding the trail of death and
destruction caused by freezing road conditions.
</P>
<P>
The wonder material can also be used in the construction of
airport runways. It will also be useful in house construction -
averting the need for any heating during traditionally cold winter
months.
</P>
<P>
The scientists in southwest China's Tibet Autonomous Region
have developed the new material which is able to efficiently
absorb and store solar energy.
</P>
<P>
They say their solar heat storage material can be used to build
highways and airport runways of the future, according to Xing
Dengqing, a senior engineer at the Tibet Solar Energy Research and
Test Center.
</P>
<P>
He said the material is made from mirabilite - a type of salt -
and borax, which are abundant in Tibet's salty lakes, together
with some other additives.
</P>
<P>
Its performance tops other materials of a similar kind in the
world and can be used for 15 to 20 years. Some similar materials
developed by foreign scientists can only last for about ten years,
Xing said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to its application in road construction, the
material has broader possibilities, the senior engineer said. It
can make light and warm clothes, and prevent freezing on major
highways, airplane runways and bridges.
</P>
<P>
It can also be used to make curtains and used together with
asphalt concrete for housing materials, with the houses built in
this way needing no heating facility in winter.
</P>
<P>
The invention will be very promising in Tibet where other forms
of energy are lacking, Xing said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
