<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slowing Price Increases in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, east China's booming
city, saw price increases slow down in 1996, according to the
lastest statistics.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the Municipal Bureau of Commodity Prices
show that the price increase range last year fell by eight
percentage points over 1995.
</P>
<P>
The retail price index and the price index of consumer goods
rose by five percent and nine percent in the whole of 1996,
respectively, far below the planned targets set by the government.
</P>
<P>
Commodity prices remained stable after May 1996 thanks to
sufficient supplies on the market. The prices of vegetables,
sugar, wine, fruit and household electric appliances even fell
to a certain degree.
</P>
<P>
Although the state readjusted the prices of crude oil and mail
services in the fourth quarter of last year, the impact was not
strong.
</P>
<P>
Prices currently controlled by the government account for
less than five percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
To sustain the slowdown of price increases, Pan Jianxin, vice
director of the Municipal Bureau of Commodity Prices, pledged to
crack down on the practice of forcing up prices, and price
cheating. 
</P>
</TEXT>
