<HEADLINE> S. Africa Sends Back Home 135,000 Illegal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Johannesburg, January 9 (Xinhua) -- More than 135,000 illegal
immigrants were sent back home in 1996, the South African
Department of Home Affairs said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
From January to November last year, 135,408 illegal immigrants,
including more than 113,000 Mozambicans, were repatriated to their
home country, a Johannesburg-based daily "The Star" reported today.
</P>
<P>
These aliens also included 13,667 Zimbabweans, 3,117 Basothos,
1,853 Malawians, 1,424 Swazis and people from another 61
countries worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Paul Alfred, Head Inspector of the Durban Border Policing and
Internal Tracing Unit, said they had their hands full during the past
year, with the arrests of 301 illegal immigrants without proper
documentation, 111 with fraudulent or expired documents, while another
16 people were caught for illegally assisting aliens by providing
employment or accommodation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Alfred said most illegal immigrants gained entry by
sneaking past border posts which were usually situated in areas
surrounded by dense bush or by entering with a visitor's permit and
then overstaying their visit.
</P>
<P>
Although the exact number of aliens currently living in South
Africa is available, the Department of Home Affairs put it
between 3.2 million and 5.2 million.
</P>
<P>
However, in terms of a cabinet decision early last year, South
Africa allowed, under certain conditions, the aliens from the Southern
African Development Community countries to apply for permament
residence in the country. enditem

=01090715

=01090718
NNNN
15:17 15:18 g # PAB
</P>
