<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Breakthrough in Preventing Prawns from Getting Epidemic Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, January 9 (Xinhua) -- New technology developed in
China has prevented prawns from contracting a deadly viral
epidemic disease.
</P>
<P>
The method has now passed a joint assessment by the Hebei
Provincial Science and Technology Commission and the Provincial
Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
The technology was developed after years of research by
Professor Wang Anli from the Biology Department of Hebei
University.
</P>
<P>
Viral epidemic disease in prawns spreads rapidly and causes a
high death toll. It is one of the key problems in the artificial
breeding of prawns.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1990s, the epidemic disease of the prawns in China
has resulted in over 10 billion yuan (1.2 billion U.S. dollars) in
direct economic losses each year.
</P>
<P>
Wang developed an agent for enhancing the immunity of the
prawns, placing it in prawn ponds during different periods of
prawn breeding.
</P>
<P>
He also suggested environmental improvement of prawn ponds in
an effort to curb the spread of the virus.
</P>
<P>
Wang and his colleagues applied the new technology in 266
hectares of prawn ponds along the coast of Tangshan City in the
past few years, and prawns in the experimental ponds survived
after the spread of epidemic diseases. Most of the prawns in other
(untreated) ponds died from the diseases.
</P>
<P>
And 1,500 kilograms of quality prawns were collected per
hectare after the application of the new technology.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 Wang carried out experiments in 3,333 hectares of ponds
in Hebei, Liaoning and Shandong provinces, with his new technology
also proving to be effective.
</P>
<P>
Prawn breeding experts have suggested the application of the
new technology nationwide.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Youths Join in Fight Against Drug Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Zambian youths have organized to
join the national fight against drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
An organization named "Youth Movement Against Drug Abuse"
(YOMADA) has been set up on the initiative of Lusaka school
leavers to supplement the State Drug Enforcement Commission
(DEC).
</P>
<P>
YOMADA's objectives will involve awareness campaigns on the
danger of drug abuse through the use of brochures, school lectures
and drama. It will hold seminars all over Zambia to sensitize
the youths on the adverse effects of drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
"While the DEC has done a commendable job in fighting the drug
abuse, there is still need to supplement their efforts through a
grassroot organization like YOMADA," said Malimba Muwela,
chairman of the youth organisation.
</P>
<P>
Drug abuse is getting rampant in Zambia. It reached pandemic
levels in 1996 in the country.
</P>
<P>
The DEC has intensified its action against drug trafficking
and drug abuse. Its offices in various parts of the country are
working the clock round. A total of 1,529 Zambians were arrested
locally and another 22 were detained in foreign countries for
trafficking of narcotic drugs in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
