<HEADLINE> 1 Israeli Soldier Killed, 8 Wounded in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 9 (Xinhua) -- One Isralei soldier was
killed and eight others wounded in a day of fierce fighting
in south Lebanon that lasted into late Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, for the second time in the past two months, at
least one Katyusha rocket landed in western Galilee of
northern Israel, though no damage or casualty was caused.
</P>
<P>
In Wednesday evening, an Israeli squad on ambush duty came
under fire from a group of Hezbullah gunmen in Shomriya
region of the central sector of the Israeli self-claimed
security zone. One soldier was killed and five others wounded
in the close-range encounter, it was not clear whether there
were casualties on the Hezbullah side.
</P>
<P>
Israeli gunners pounded Hezbullah targets in exchanges that
continued for several hours, with Hezbullah gunmen also shelling
Israeli troop positions in the eastern sector.
</P>
<P>
After the katyusha rocket attack, Israeli warplanes struck at
Hezbullah targets north of the zone. An Israeli army spoeksman
said that the pilots reported accurate hits of the targets.
But Hezbullah denied responsibility for launching the Katyusha
attack.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, three Israeli soldiers were wounded after
one of them stepped on a mine near Soujud in the
northeastern sector of the zone. The soldier who detonated the
anti-personnel mine lost a foot in the explosion.
</P>
<P>
Israeli warplanes launched retaliatory attacks against Hezbullah
targets after the incident, while Hezbullah returned mortars at
Israeli positions.
</P>
<P>
Amiram Levine, Israeli army's northern commander, issued a
stern warning Wednesday night to Hezbullah that it was
"walking a tightrope" and would lead to a heavy Israeli
response to its recent escalation in hostilities.
</P>
<P>
He blamed Hezbullah for violating the ceasefire understandings
reached after April's Grapes of Wrath operation by firing from
villages.
</P>
<P>
Livine said that there was a limit to Israel's restraint
and it might prove necessary to hit back harder to cease
the firing. And in that case, Hezbullah should be held
solely responsible for bringing the fighting into civilian
areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
