<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Intensify Investment Campaign in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe is planning to initiate
an investment campaign in 1997 to draw fresh incentives for its
national economic development.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that from January to October last year, 920
million U.S. Dollars had been invested in the country, creating
9,038 jobs and representing a significant growth over the same
period in 1995.
</P>
<P>
"The year of 1997 poses very good prospects for investment.
However, our ability to attract investment will be underpinned by
the promotional activities that we will undertake," said Nicholas
Ncube, Executive Director of the Zimbabwe Investment Center,
</P>
<P>
Ncube urged the government to expedite the launch of the
second phase of the economic reform program to boost investor
confidence and set the pace for economic development as the
country moves towards the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the government is campaigning to improve
investors' confidence and to lower high interest rates which were
considered major barriers to foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Further liberalisation of exchange controls, an improvement in
the telecommunication services and macro-economic stability would
also enhance the country's investment campaigns, he noted.
</P>
