<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Help For Poor Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- China has issued more
funds to aid poor college and university students who excel,
today's China Youth Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the 400,000-yuan stipend has gone to
outstanding students majoring in agriculture, forestry, water
conservancy, geology and mining, oil and gas, as well as coal,
metallurgy and mapping.
</P>
<P>
The Central Committee of the Communist Youth League of China
launched the move together with the All-China Students'
Federation, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
It was hailed by students with financial difficulties, the
paper quoted Han Huipeng, deputy director of the Education
Department of the Ministry of Agriculture, as saying.
</P>
<P>
A survey showed that among the total college enrollments, poor
students account for an average 20 percent, including seven
percent with great financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of poor students in some colleges attached to the
Ministry of the Coal Industry and the Ministry of Forestry
respectively were 30 percent and 10 percent, and 17.8 percent in
agriculture-related colleges.
</P>
<P>
The paper added that the first segment of a 1.2 million yuan
fund was issued to poor students in 29 higher learning
institutions in the 11 provinces last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
