<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Has Most Urban Phone Users in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital registered
450,000 more urban telephone users in 1996, bringing the total
number to 1.95 million.
</P>
<P>
There are now 29 telephones for every 100 people in Beijing,
and among the urban city dwellers the figure is 42 per 100, ranking
in first place among Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
Officials are predicting that every household in Beijing is
expected to have phone access by the year 2000. If every household
has at least one phone, there will be 42 phones for every 100
people, and in the urban districts the figure will reach 62, with
local switchboards having a handling capacity of 70 million lines.
</P>
<P>
In contrast to poor services in the telephone sector, the city
has vowed to improve its image by cutting the phone installation
time to within three months for urban users and 45 days for
suburban users.
</P>
<P>
If telephone applicants hand over installation fees, but
cannot get phone access for six months, the applicant will be
exempted from routine service charges for one month.
</P>
<P>
Private phones now account for 71.3 percent of the total figure
in China. About half of households in China's largest metropolis
of Shanghai have phones.
</P>
<P>
China readjusted rates for its telephone services last
December, with charges reduced for international phone calls, and
costs increased for calls within cities.
</P>
<P>
The country added 15 million lines to its telephone switching
capacity in 1996, bringing the total to 100 million lines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Government to Inject Funds into Property Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Finance Ministry is to
start injecting 70 billion baht (2.8 billion U.S. dollars) into
the ailing property sector this month to boost market and
liquidity.
</P>
<P>
For this purpose, a 50-billion-baht (2 billion dollar)
resolution trust fund will be established to help projects with
liquidity problems, according to Finance Minister Amnuay Virawan,
who is also a deputy prime minister in charge of financial
matters.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the fund was one of the four measures
adopted Wednesday at a joint meeting of the Finance Ministry, the
Bank of Thailand, the Government Savings Bank and the Government
Housing Bank.
</P>
<P>
Finance companies, commercial banks and the Bank of Thailand
will contribute jointly to the fund to buy such projects.
</P>
<P>
The measure also aims to lift foreign investor confidence in
local financial institutes and reduce non-performing loans
extended to developers.
</P>
<P>
The assistance, which will initially last for one year, will be
extended only to projects with liquidity problems but with growth
potential. Those that appear doomed will not enjoy the privilege.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the resolution trust fund, the Government
Housing Bank, the Government Savings Bank and the Bank of Thailand
will establish a 20-billion-baht (800 million dollar) fund to
extend low-interest loans to government and state enterprise
officials to buy their first homes.
This measure is aimed at absorbing excess housing.
</P>
<P>
The third measure is the formation of a secondary mortgage
corporation to further boost liquidity in the property sector,
which has been sluggish for at least three years.
</P>
<P>
Under the measure, land or house used as collateral for loans
for housing estates will be allowed to be made into credit
instruments to mobilize funds from the financial market.
</P>
<P>
However, a law will be needed to put this measure into effect
and the process will be time-consuming.
</P>
<P>
As the last measure, the government will support its agencies
and state enterprises to buy completed office buildings and those
due to be completed within this year.
</P>
<P>
This measure will encourage additional demand.
</P>
<P>
The Land Department will be asked to stop issuing new property
licenses.
</P>
<P>
Restrictions on foreign ownership of land would also be
relaxed, opening the way for foreign investors to purchase homes
for personal use.
</P>
<P>
A foreigner can now purchase up to one rai (0.16 hectares) of
land, but only with the approval of the Interior Minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
