<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Lanka To Seek More Flights To Indian Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Air Lanka, Sri Lanka's national
airline, will seek more flights to Indian cities at civil aviation
talks due later this month, Air Lanka official sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that Air Lanka will in particular seek
permission to fly to Bangalore and Hyderabad, the cities in south
India where business is booming.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, Air Lanka's two flights to New Delhi
every week are doing well as they are the only direct flights
between the two South Asian capitals, Colombo and New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
Air Lanka wants now to introduce a third weekly flight to cope
with the rush. As many as 42 ambassadors and high commissioners
based in New Delhi are concurrently accredited to Colombo and
often commute between the two capitals, the sources pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Air Lanka now flies to five Indian cities -- New Delhi, Mumbai
(Bombay), Chennai (Madras), Thiruvananthapuramm (Trivandrum) and
Trichy (Tiruchchitappalli). All flights are reported to be going
full.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that Sri Lanka now wants to suggest to the
Indian authorities that the number of seats be increased from
3,500 per week at present to 5,500 on its flights from Colombo to
India and India to Colombo as well.
</P>
<P>
This means that Air Lanka is expecting to fly 286,000
passengers a year from Colombo to India and as many from India to
Sri Lanka, an increase of 64 percent in seat capacity.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the demand for an increase in seat
capacity indicates that more Sri Lankans and Indians are visiting
each other's countries for business, holidays and pilgrimages.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan businessmen buy Indian goods worth 500 million U.S.
dollars every year. Many of them travel to India on a regular
basis. In the same manner, a large number of Indian businessmen
also travel to Sri Lanka, the sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
