<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cargo Handling Declines at Chittagong Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Cargo handling at Chittagong Port,
the biggest sea port in Bangladesh, declined for the first time in
four years in 1996 by 12.17 percent, according to Port Authority
sources.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the turn-around of the vessels decreased to
4.69 days in 1996 from 5.07 days in 1995. The handling of vessels
also declined from 1,444 in 1995 to 1,384 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
A total of 11.077 million tons of import and export cargo were
handled in this port in 1995 while only 9.562 million tons of
cargo was handled in 1996, over 1.514 million tons less than the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, the import of fertilizer, salt, sugar
and edible oil increased in 1996 while that of food grain, cement,
coal and petroleum products declined.
</P>
<P>
Among the export goods, jute goods, tea, frozen goods, naptha
and ammonia declined while leather goods, ready-made garments and
fertilizer increased. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Railway Transport on Decline in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Trains carried 942 million
travelers in 1996, a 12.3 percent drop from the previous year,
latest statistics issued by China's Ministry of Railways have
revealed.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1.62 billion tons of cargo were delivered by railway
transport last year, up 1.4 percent. Statistics show that trains
transported 720 million tons of coal in 1996, 46.6 million tons
more than in 1995. The transport volume of other goods dropped by
23.7 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Competition in the country's transportation market is becoming
fiercer. More travelers are turning from rail to air, bus or
waterways for faster and cheaper services.
</P>
<P>
The ministry predicts that 920 million people will travel by
train in 1997, and 1.61 to 1.62 billion tons of cargo will be
moved by rail, bringing the annual revenue from railway transport
to 78.5 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Rail income, however, is still on the rise, due mainly to
increasing numbers of travelers preferring sleeping cars, which
provide a more comfortable service, and also higher charges for
hard seats. Early last year ticket prices for train sleepers were
nearly doubled, and the prices for hard seats were slightly
increased.
</P>
<P>
Rail transport contributed revenues of 75.6 billion yuan last
year, up nearly 20 percent over 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
