<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Jailed Ex-President May Be Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's former president
Hossain Mohammad Ershad is expected to be set free today after
spending more than 6 years in jail following a bail granted by the
supreme court in the radar purchase case Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ershad, who took power as president of the military regime in
Bangladesh in 1982, was taken into custody within 6 days after his
forced step-down on December 6, 1990 and implicated in as many as
19 corruption and criminal cases by the previous government of
Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP).
</P>
<P>
So far, Ershad, the 69 year-old general, was granted bails in
17 cases.
</P>
<P>
"Pending disposal of the appeal, let the accused-petitioner be
released on ad-interim bail to the satisfaction of the deputy
commissioner (of the Dhaka Central Jail)," ordered the full bench
of the supreme court including Chief Justice A.T.M. Afzal while
granting the bail to Ershad in the radar purchase case.
</P>
<P>
Ershad is likely to be freed from prison today on completion of
necessary formalities, his counsel Yousuf Hossain Humayun said.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Jatiya (national) Party, of which Ershad has
been the chairman, also confirmed that their leader is likely to
be released in the afternoon around 02:00 PM after his counsel and
his young brother Golam Kadar furnish the bail bonds at the deputy
commissioner's office and the JP is planning a reception for their
chief.
</P>
<P>
It was learnt that the move to release Ershad has produced
mixed reaction among different political quarters.
</P>
<P>
The mainstream opposition BNP said that there had been a tacit
understanding between the ruling Awami League and the JP since
1982 and charged that the ruling party said many things against
corruption, but they were releasing the corrupt people.
</P>
<P>
Ershad was granted bail as the court deemed it fit and there
was nothing to be surprised about it, General Secretary of the
ruling Awami League Zillur Rahman said, adding that the law would
take its own course and it was the normal practice throughout the
world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
