<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Considers Roving Diplomats for Remote Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The Thai foreign Ministry is
considering to send Bangkok-based officials as roving ambassadors
to remote countries in Africa, South America and the breakaway
republics of the former Soviet Union, instead of opening embassies
there.
</P>
<P>
The idea took shape after the ministry ordered a temporary
closure of the Thai Embassy in Nigeria on November 30 last year
due to safety reasons, according to local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Permanent Secretary for Foreign Affairs Sakthip
Krairiksh said that the unwillingness of officials to be stationed
in these countries also fueled the idea of sending short-term
diplomatic missions to the countries.
</P>
<P>
The missions will be sent twice a year and last a few weeks
each time, Sakthip said, adding that the measure will make the
officials more enthusiastic about their work.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's ambassadors-at-large, directors-general, and
deputy permanent secretaries for foreign affairs who intend to
serve in Bangkok for several years would be eligible for such
missions, Sakthip said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, local newspapers said that Thailand has five
embassies in Africa and they are in Egypt, Kenya, Morocco, Senegal
and South Africa to oversee 50 countries there.
</P>
<P>
In South America, Thailand has three embassies, respectively in
Argentina, Brazil and Chile.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
