<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IPR Cases Get Close Scrutiny by Law Courts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The number of law suits
involving infringement of intellectual property rights (IPR)
handled by Chinese courts is increasing, a senior judge in charge
of IPR cases told China Daily.
</P>
<P>
During the first ten months of last year, Chinese courts heard
341 cases concerning copyrights, up 6.2 percent over the same
period of 1995; 493 computer software cases, up 36.9 percent; 251
trademark infringement cases, up 22 percent; and 845 patent
infringement cases, up 14 percent, said Li Guoguang,
vice-president of the Supreme People's Court.
</P>
<P>
Some new IPR cases, such as infringement on the use of person's
name and infringement of computer software trademarks, have also
occurred, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese courts intend to strengthen the protection of IPR this
year, Li said, pledging that offenders will be punished according
to law.
</P>
<P>
The courts intend to co-operated and exchange information more
frequently with law circles in other countries, introduce Chinese
experiences and learn from foreign practices, Li said.
</P>
<P>
China's judicial protection of IPR has developed rapidly in
recent years. From 1991 to June 1996, the courts handled some
20,000 civil IPR cases, 90 percent of which have been resolved, Li
said. About three percent of these cases involved overseas
litigants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
