<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Cabinet Reshuffle Sees Backfire in Ruling Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 9 (Xinhua) -- A cabinet reshuffle by Prime
Minister Sher Bahadur Deuba Wednesday has seen backfire from his
main ruling Nepali Congress (NC) party, the local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Deuba's decision to reinstate four resigned ministers from the
National Democratic Party (RPP), the second largest ruling partner
of the coalition government, stunned his NC party colleagues who
earlier asked him not to do so, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
In a move to stabilize his three-party government, Deuba
Wednesday reshuffled his cabinet, or council of ministers, to
reinstate several resigned ministers, who last month quit the
cabinet and voted in favor of an opposition-tabled no-confidence
motion against the government in parliament.
</P>
<P>
NC party president Girija Prasad Koirala, who was in the
eastern Nepali city of Biratnagar, Wednesday publicly criticized
the prime minister through telephone after learning about the
cabinet reshuffle, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
"I totally disagree with your choices of the ministers. You
will soon face the consequence of this move (reshuffle)," the NC
president was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, Koirala declined to say whether his party would take
action against Prime Minister Deuba, who is also parliamentary
leader of the NC party.
</P>
<P>
A group of NC MPs early this week warned Deuba against
reinstatement of the resigned RPP ministers, who on Monday
reasserted their support for the government after the
no-confidence motion tabled by the Communist Party of Nepal
(United Marxist Leninist, CPN-UML), the main opposition, was
rejected last month by the lower house.
</P>
<P>
The resigned ministers sat on the opposition bench during a
special house session on the no-confidence motion two weeks ago
and voted in favor of the motion.
</P>
<P>
The MPs from Deuba's own party threatened to vote against the
government when it seeks a vote of confidence in parliament later
if Deuba reinstates these "immoral" RPP lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
Deuba's three-party government has been reduced with only
minority parliament support as 101 MPs voted for and 84 MPs
against the opposition-sponsored censure motion in the 205-seat
house last month.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that Deuba would seek a vote of confidence for
his government in the upcoming winter session of parliament, which
will probably begin in February, 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
