<HEADLINE> Italy Keeps Inflation Falling in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Italy experienced a downward
inflation throughout last year, according to figures released
today by Italian statistics institute (Istat).
</P>
<P>
The year 1996 saw an average inflation rate of 3.9 percent: 5.5
percent in January and 2.6 percent in December.
</P>
<P>
But officials of Istat also confirmed the warning of Prime
Minister Romano Prodi who said Tuesday that figures of this
January may not be so good as those of recent months.
</P>
<P>
They attributed this situation largely to technical reasons
seeing that new items for calculating the inflation rate was
introduced, which were expected to push the rate up to 2.7 or 2.8
percent in January.
</P>
<P>
However, Prodi predicted that the figures would once again be
"good" in February. 
</P>
