<HEADLINE> Sandinista Warns of Protest in Nicaragua Against Supreme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Angered by a Supreme Court
decision of wiping out dozens of laws, Nicaragua's Sandinista
leader Daniel Ortega warned today of protest in the country.
</P>
<P>
Ortega, speaking in the final session of the outgoing National
Assembly, said his party would launch even violent protest to
defend the stricken laws.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court overturned by a 9-3 vote Tuesday night all
the bills approved by the Sandinista Front of National Liberation
Party and its allies in the National Assembly since November 22,
including the 1997 budget bill, the tax reform bill and the
procedure bill.
</P>
<P>
The bills were passed during the last session of the outgoing
National Assembly, which were boycotted by legislators who
supported Sandinista's rival Arnoldo Aleman, the president-elected.
</P>
<P>
Aleman, who is also the head of the Liberal Alliance coalition,
will be inaugurated Friday.
</P>
<P>
Calling the Supreme Court ruling "a coup d'etat", Sandinista
congressman Rafael Solis said the decision will affect the
economic growth in the country, provoke instability and encourage
people to disregard institutions.
</P>
<P>
"It puts the country in a crisis situation with unpredictable
consequences," he added.
</P>
<P>
Ortega, who was president of the Latin American country during
the 1979-1990 Sandinista government, accused the Supreme Court of
conspiring to strike down the laws and "break the constitutional
order" and called for the removal of Supreme Court magistrates.
</P>
<P>
He would not say whether protests were planned for Aleman's
inauguration, which was to be held in Managua's Rigoberto Lopez
Perez Stadium.
</P>
<P>
Security has been tightened around the stadium and some key
plazas and hotels as well.
</P>
<P>
Aleman, former mayor of the country's capital of Managua, takes
power among high hopes and predictions of soaring economic
growth. But tough challenges remain as he has inherited the second
poorest country in Latin American. 
</P>
</TEXT>
