<HEADLINE> Chile to Increase Investment in Forestry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Chilean government
announced today it will increase the investment in forestry to 236
billion pesos (575.6 million U.S. dollars) this year, 34.241
billion pesos (83.5 million dollars) more than that of 1996, to
support this weak sector.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Minister Carlos Mladinic said focus will be placed
on improving and protecting natural resources and updating
technology, with 52.144 billion pesos (127.1 million dollars) and
41.374 billion pesos (100.9 million dollars) allotted to each of
them.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 48.071 billion pesos (117.2 million dollars) will
be used in developing water resources and irrigation, and 1.09
billion pesos (2.6 million dollars) in opening up new markets.
</P>
<P>
Highlighting the sustained growth of farm exports which in 1996
totaled 2.478 billion dollars, about 18.3 percent over 1995,
Mladinic said, the most dynamic sectors of fruit, vegetable, wine
and dairy helped offset the poor performance of forestry. 
</P>
