<HEADLINE> Cyclone Approaching NZ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand MetService
has warned that the northern part of North Island will be hit by
18 hours of torrential rain and winds gusting up to 130 km an
hour.
</P>
<P>
It said Cyclone Drena, now passing Norfolk Island east of
Australia, will reach the north of North Island tomorrow morning.
</P>
<P>
MetService chief forecaster Angie Auger advised campers in the
far north to go home now because Drena has the potential to be
more damaging than that of Cyclone Fergus, which produced heavy
damage to the middle part of North Island at the end of last
month.
</P>
<P>
Drena would bring severe flooding and slips on the main routes
in the north and cause rivers and estuaries there to swell.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, civil defense staff are busy getting ready for the
imminent cyclone. Staff members, the police, and fire and
ambulance services are being supplied with the latest weather
information, TVNZ reported.  
</P>
