<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Government Offers New Funds for Farmers in Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government has made new
funds available to farmers to clear their debts incurred on the
so-called "unorganized" money market.
</P>
<P>
The government-owned bank for agriculture and agricultural
cooperatives (BAAC) has allocated 2 billion baht (80 million US
dollars) to make loans to farmers over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
Farmers who have borrowed from local loan sharks or mortgaged
their land with unorganized lending sources can apply for BAAC
loans and can use the proceeds to redeem the mortgaged land.
</P>
<P>
The loans would be for a maximum of 200,000 to 300,000 baht
(8,000 to 12,000 dollars), with 8 percent annual interest and
repayment periods of 10-15 years.
</P>
<P>
It is the second attempt by the BAAC to help free farmers from
the grip of the unorganized money market.
</P>
<P>
Two years ago, it determined that about 4,500 farmers had this
particular kind of debt problem, and it spent two billion baht to
help them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
