<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Readmitted to Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
was readmitted to hospital Wednesday night after developing signs
of pneumonia, the Russian Presidential Press Service said today.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin caught a flu early this week and has been staying in
bed since then. On Wednesday evening, doctors detected the first
signs of pneumonia during a routine examination and decided
Yeltsin needed to be hospitalized for several days.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin had a bypass surgery early November last year. But his
doctors insisted that his current condition was unrelated to his
heart problems or the surgery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Majority Leader Reveals New Congress Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Senate majority leader
Trent Lott said today that the Congress in its new term will focus
on a Republican 10-bill package, including some 150 billion
U.S. dollars of tax cuts and a balanced budget amendment.
</P>
<P>
The 105th Congress took oath into office Tuesday with a
Republican majority in both the Senate and the House. Republican
Newt Gingrich was re-elected speaker of the House and Lott keeps
the post of the Senate majority leader.
</P>
<P>
The 10-bill package will be introduced the day after President
Bill Clinton's inauguration on January 20, Lott told the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce today.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We are committed to a balanced budget constitutional
amendment," adding that "I believe we're going to come up with a
balanced budget plan this year that will get us to a balanced
budget over a period of years by the year 2002."
</P>
<P>
Tax cuts, which the Republican Congress and the Democratic
Administration were fighting for in the past years, will be
incorporated into the package, probably including relief for
families with children, reduction of capital gains and estate
taxes, said Lott.
</P>
<P>
"We need still more tax fairness in the tax code... I'd like to
see us obviously cut capital gains tax rates and not just the part
that applies to homes," he said, adding that some 150 billion
dollars' tax cuts over a couple of years could promote growth.
</P>
<P>
Lott said Clinton has made a good start by proposing to
eliminate capital gains taxes on most home sales but "knows he's
going to have to do better than that,"
</P>
<P>
During budget talks early last year, Clinton indicated a
willingness to approve a broader-based capital gains cut as part
of an overall budget deal.
</P>
<P>
Other likely bills are an anti-crime bill providing the death
penalty for so-called drug kingpins, a ban on certain late-term
abortion and permission for companies to offer compensatory time
off instead of paid overtime, Lott said.
</P>
<P>
He also said renewal of the Superfund program to clean up toxic
waste sites and changes in product liability laws would be other
priorities in the new legislative discussions.
</P>
<P>
He added that there could be an early action on giving the
president fast-track authority to negotiate international trade
agreements.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the House on Tuesday, Gingrich also stressed tax-cut
issue, saying, "Whether we go towards a flat tax, or whether we
replace the income tax with a sales tax, or what we do. But to
begin a process that frankly may take four to six years, but is
the right direction for the right reason." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
