<HEADLINE> Thailand's Industrial Exports Up 0.7 Percent in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's export value of
industrial goods last year was only 0.7 percent higher than in
1995, falling far short of the 8 percent growth target.
</P>
<P>
The business economics department blamed global economic
slowdown, volatile fluctuations of the dollar and yen and high
production costs for the disappointing export performance.
</P>
<P>
However, the department predicted that exports of Thai
industrial products would grow 10 percent in 1997, from 844
billion baht (33.76 billion US dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The department based brighter prospects for the sector on a
global economic recovery, government initiatives to make Thai
products more competitive, and the fruition of efforts begun in
the third quarter of 1996 to boost the value of exports.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's overall exports growth in 1996 were expected to be
near zero.
</P>
<P>
To reduce the trade and current account deficit, the Commerce
Ministry is considering restrictions on imports of luxury
products, such as many types of consumer goods and automobiles,
which are not essential and hurt the local economy.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will also launch 'buy Thai' campaigns to encourage
people to buy Thai products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
