<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll Sets Fashtion in Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Swimming has become one of the
favorite sports in Costa Rica, a soccer-mad country, and that's
mostly because of a tall, slim girl: Claudia Poll.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old freestyler, winner of the women's 200m
freestyle of the Beijing Leg World Cup Short-Course Wednesday,
grabbed the first Olympic gold in Atlanta last summer for her tiny
South American nation, which only has a population of three
million.
</P>
<P>
She won the women's 200 meter freestyle in 1:58.16.
</P>
<P>
"Now In Costa Rica quite lot of young people are interested in
swimming, specially those young ladies, " said Francisco Ricos,
who began to coach Claudia when she was seven.
</P>
<P>
"Swimming has come into fashion in my country and I know that's
due to Claudia," the coach added.
</P>
<P>
Claudia shot to prominence when she shattered the 200m
freestyle world record at the World Short-Course Championships in
Rio De Janeiro, Brazil, in December, 1995.
</P>
<P>
Silvia Poll, Claudia's elder sister, is also a swimming star
and favor in Costa Rica, but has never succeeded like Claudia --
an Olympic crown -- before her retirement in two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Silvia, nicknamed Magic girl, clinched a silver medal in the
200m freestyle at the Seoul Olympic Games in 1988.
</P>
<P>
For Claudia, swimming has been dominating over her all
things. She could hardly imagine what's her life like without
swimming.
</P>
<P>
"She likes swimming, even crazy about it, and works hard,"
Ricos said.
</P>
<P>
"She began a new training program after winning the Olympic
gold and never kept herself away from training since then. Can you
imagine that?"
</P>
<P>
Beijing is her second major international competition since the
Atlanta Games. She participated the Hong Kong leg World Cup
Short-Course tournament, where she accumulated a total of three
golds and one silver.
</P>
<P>
Claudia also added a silver medal in the 800m freestyle to her
gold Wednesday when she was beaten by a surprising winner Lin
Chi-chan of Chinese Taipei.
</P>
<P>
"The long distance event is quite different from the middle
one," Claudia explained.
</P>
<P>
the 200m and 400m are Claudia's strongest events. "She is the
world number one in the two disciplines," her coach said. Anyway,
Ricos was quite satisfied with her timing because she swam her
personal best time in the event.
</P>
<P>
But the confident swimmer wants more.
</P>
<P>
"I always take myslef as the number one opponent. I like to
make challenge to myself," said Claudia, who made entries in total
of four events here.
</P>
<P>
She wants to find out more strong events. The 800m freestyle
was one of those attempts though she has fewer chance than she won
in the 100m. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
