<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Seeking Foreign Investment in Mineral-Based </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 9 (Xinhua) --The Sri Lankan government has
called for foreign investment in the country's mineral resources
sector, Industrial Development Ministry sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that development of the mineral resources
sector requires large capital investment and involves high risks
and therefore the sector has been dominated by corporate giants
capable of spreading risks over large geographic and commodity
areas.
</P>
<P>
Foreign participation is therefore essential for the
development of mineral-based industries, the sources noted.
</P>
<P>
Three Japanese firms had shown interest in "quartz" while other
countries such as Norway, Korea, Japan, Australia and the US were
keen on investing in mineral sands, other minerals and salt,
according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
The Geological Survey and Mines Bureau (GSMB) of Sri Lanka has
made special facilities to meet the needs of investors in the
mineral sector.
</P>
<P>
The services of several World Bank consultants have been
obtained to work with the GSMB on geological exploration as well
as to advise on additional regulations required for the safety of
workers, according to the sources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
