<HEADLINE> Tajik Commander Disobeys Order to Return to Barracks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Tensions increased again in
war-torn Tajikistan Wednesday as a brigade commander of the
country's rapid reaction forces refused to return to barracks as
ordered by the president.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from Dushanbe, capital of the mountainous
republic, Colonel Makhmud Khudoyberdyev, who led an
anti-government revolt a year ago, ignored a deadline given by
President Imomali Rakhmonov to start pulling out his troops back
to its base in the southern town of Kurgan-Tyubeto by 16:00 local
time (11:00GMT) Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The brigadier instead moved his troops and arms towards an
aluminium plant in the town of Tursunzade, some 54 kilometers west
of Dushanbe.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Khudoyberdyev's troops clashed with an armed band led
by a local strongman. Khudoyberdyev said his troops had moved to
Tursunzade to disarm the band which had stolen weapons from his
troops.
</P>
<P>
Khudoyberdyev was apparently targeting the aluminium plant in
Tursunzade and the eastern part of the town. The commander
demanded that the administrator of the town be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
Tursunzade, which produced some 237,000 tons of aluminium in
1995, has been the site of clashes between armed groups fighting
to control Tajikistan's metal trade.
</P>
<P>
Reports said a reason Khudoyberdyev refused to obey Rakhmonov's
order to withdraw was that the government was slow to investigate
the killing of one of his men late last month.
</P>
<P>
First Deputy Prime Minister Abdurakhmon Azimov has left for
Tursunzade to hold talks with representatives from the concerned
parties.
</P>
<P>
The peacekeeping force stationed there also began mediating
between the parties on Wednesday in an effort to find a peaceful
settlement.
</P>
<P>
The Tajik government this week has been holding peace talks
with the Islamic opposition in the Iranian capital Tehran. The two
sides have signed several ceasefire agreements since civil war
broke out in 1992, but a lasting peace has never achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
