<HEADLINE> Aid Scheme Helps Poor Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Living on less than 100 yuan (12
US dollars) each month in Beijing means that finding sufficient
food and proper maintenance can on many occasion create dilemmas
for the very best and brightest students.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, about ten percent of the 3,000 students in the
Beijing Forestry University must manage to survive on that meager
sum, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the poverty line in Beijing soars high about
at 170 yuan (22 US dollars) per month.
</P>
<P>
Throughout the country, about seven percent of the total three
million college students are trapped by such grinding poverty.
The Chinese Communist Youth League Central Committee estimates the
average student survives on about 120 yuan (14 US dollars) per
month.
</P>
<P>
The committee yesterday distributed 400,000 yuan (48,000 US
dollars) in relief aid to financially trapped college students in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
About 500 of the poorest students across the country will
receive 800 yuan (96 US dollars) subsidy each, including some from
the Beijing Forestry University. Last year the number was 630 in
29 colleges and universities of 11 provinces and autonomous
regions.
</P>
<P>
This is the second consecutive year the youth authority has
reached out to help students trapped by insufficient funds and the
high cost of living.
</P>
<P>
This year, the money will go to schools under the ministries of
geology and mineral resources, coal industry, metallurgical
industry and agriculture and other organizations.
</P>
<P>
The government and schools try to make sure that not a single
college student drops out of school because of poverty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0257 </DOCNO>
