<HEADLINE> Top '96 Film Events Announced in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The magazine Popular Cinema has
listed ten most significant events in Chinese film-making in 1996,
today's China Daily reported. They are:
</P>
<P>
1. Jiang Zemin, general-secretary of the Communist Party of
China, inspected the August First Film Studio on June 10. Jiang
encouraged film artists to shoot more excellent films to help
promote ethical and cultural progress.
</P>
<P>
2. The "Film Administrative Regulations" were put into effect
on July 1. The regulations were adopted to manage China's film
production, examination, import, export, distribution and
projection.
</P>
<P>
3. The National Film Working Conference was held on March 23-26
at Changsha, Hunan province. The conference launched the "9550
Project" -- that is, to shoot 50 top feature films during the
Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
4. Outstanding film artists Shui Hua, Bai Yang, Chen Huangmei
and Zhang Junxiang passed away. Their images and merits will be
remembered by millions of film fans.
</P>
<P>
5. The film "Red Cherry" won the top prizes of the "Golden
Rooster Film Awards," "Hundred Flowers Film Awards" and "China
Huabiao Film Awards." Directed by Ye Daying and made by the
Beijing Youth Film Studio, the film tells how the children of
Chinese leaders and revolutionaries studied and fought in the
Ivanov International Children's School of the former Soviet Union
from 1940 to 1945.
</P>
<P>
6. The Changchun Film Studio, known as the cradle of New
China's film industry, celebrated its 50th birthday.
</P>
<P>
7. "Trials of Strength," a large-scale documentary film
reflecting the war to resist US aggression and aid Korea
(1950-53), created a box-office record in Guangzhou and other
cities.
</P>
<P>
8. "Uproar in Heaven," a full-length mythical feature film
which focuses on the rebellious spirit of the Monkey King, started
shooting by using both trick photography and special digital
computer technology.
</P>
<P>
9. A number of films and TV series were made to mark the 60th
anniversary of the success of the epic Long March.
</P>
<P>
10. Quite a few films and TV series started shooting to usher
in China's resumption of the exercise of Hong Kong's sovereignty
on July 1, 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
