<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overheating Threat Still Looms in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Bank Indonesia (central bank)
Governor J. Soedradjad Djiwandono said the national economy has
started to cool but warned that a relaxed monetary stance could
cause it to overheat again.
</P>
<P>
The governor told an annual bankers dinner here last night that
monetary policy this year would continue to focus on strengthening
internal and external macroeconomics stability.
</P>
<P>
Overheating still overshadowed Indonesia's economy in 1996, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
High imports had worsened deficit of current account, money
supply growth was high and banks have over spent on property and
consumer sectors, he added.
</P>
<P>
People should be vigilant on the rising current account
deficit, he said. The deficit, which stood at 8.8 billion US
dollars, is expected to reach 9.8 billion US dollars in 1997/98
fiscal year beginning on April 1.
</P>
<P>
He also warned about the rapid growth of private offshore
borrowing, which constituted almost 50 percent of the country's
outstanding foreign debt of 110 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's debt service ratio -- the ratio of debt servicing
obligations to export revenue -- is 31.7 percent, of which 15.5
percent is contributed by the private sector.
</P>
<P>
An inefficient use of foreign borrowings would only create
future problems given the large foreign debt and high debt service
ratio, the governor said.
</P>
<P>
"Our high priority is to cool down the economic overheating
while avoiding drastic measures that could pose unintended
shocks," he said.
</P>
<P>
The government, he said, has been trying to maintain a balanced
budget to achieve substantial government saving for repaying
external debt service and funding development.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would maintain a prudent monetary
policy. Inflation rate would be kept at a low rate which in 1996
reached 6.5 percent. The rate in the previous year was 8.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
The economic growth would remain at over 7 percent in 1997. The
main objective is to keep domestic demand growth in line with
economic capacity, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the country's economic growth was estimated to be at
7.8 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
