<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lizard Fossil Found in Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, January 8 (Xinhua) -- A group of paleontologists
have found the fossilized remains of a lizard between 800,000 and
2 million years old in the province of Buenos Aires, in eastern
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
The reptile probably belonged to the Teidas family which grows
to between 10-15 centimeters long, Argentina's Telam News Agency
quoted an expert as saying.
</P>
<P>
Orland Scaglia, chief of the municipal Museum of Natural
Sciences in the city of Mar del Plata, said that the fossilized
remains of the lizard were found last November in a ravine near
the coast in the city of Mar del Plata.
</P>
<P>
The discovery of a reptile fossil in tertiary or quaternary
sediments -- like this one of a lizard -- is a very rare
paleontological event, said the expert. 
</P>
</TEXT>
