<HEADLINE> Chavalit Unveils Government's Business Philosophy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh Wednesday stressed that deregulation, liberalization
and privatization are the three key elements of his government's
fundamental business philosophy, while foreign investors could
expect more relaxed rules for them.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit unveiled the key elements at a luncheon here when Thai
economic ministers met the foreign chambers of commerce.
</P>
<P>
Privatization of state enterprises will be accelerated and
foreign investors will be allowed to hold an ownership share of
15-30 percent in state enterprises, Chavalit said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investments in state enterprises will help cut the
country's current account deficit, he added.
</P>
<P>
Deputy prime minister Amnuay Virawan echoed the prime
minister's statement that liberalization of all sectors would be
the government's goal over the next two years, according to local
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The government is considering relaxing the alien business law
and shareholding regulations to ease foreign entry into certain
industries, he said.
</P>
<P>
Amnuay also announced at the luncheon that restrictions on
foreign ownership of land would be relaxed, paving the way for
foreign investors to buy houses for personal use.  
</P>
</TEXT>
