<HEADLINE> Guatemala's Court Appealed to Suspend Amnesty Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Alliance
Against Impunity in Guatemala today presented a legal petition to
the constitutional court for a partial suspension of the National
Reconciliation Bill.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Guatemala City, capital of Guatemala, said the
alliance, with the participation of the 1992 Nobel peace
prize-winner Rigoberta Menchu Tum, said that the amnesty bill
violates at least three articles of the country's constitution.
</P>
<P>
The petition was aimed at preventing the ordinary crimes
committed by servicemen and guerrillas from avoiding punishments.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the alliance said the Reconciliation Bill violates
three articles of the constitution, including guarantees for
individual rights, people's access to justice and the duties of
the congress.
</P>
<P>
Hellen Mack, leader of the Mirna Mack Foundation and the
alliance, said the amnesty bill was manipulated to favor
servicemen who are trying to avoid trials for the massacres and
assassination of peasant, leaders of unions and students as well
as other crimes.
</P>
<P>
Rigoberta Menchu Tum also said the controversial law has
several "loopholes" that should be cleared up so that the society,
shattered by the civil war, might reach real reconciliation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
