<HEADLINE> Panama Canal to Make $100 Million Extra Profit in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Panama Canal will earn
more than 100 million U.S. dollars of extra income from its direct
profits in the year 2000, Panama Canal administrator Alberto
Aleman Zubieta said today.
</P>
<P>
"The canal is in a process of development, expansion and
improvement that will continue until the year 2005," Zubieta said.
</P>
<P>
Increase in toll charges will be the prime source of the extra
income.
</P>
<P>
The board of directors of the Panama Canal has agreed to
increase toll charges by 8.2 percent this year and by another 7.5
percent in 1998 as part of a two-stage financial restructuring
program.
</P>
<P>
A latest report from the canal authorities showed that income
from the canal in the 1996 fiscal year will amount to 463 million
dollars. And Zubieta also predicted the total income will exceed
500 million dollars in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The administrator said the definitive return of the
transoceanic canal on the part of the United States in accordance
with the 1977 Torrijos-Carter Treaties will also be conducive to
the increase of additional income.
</P>
<P>
"Panama will own 100 percent of the shares of the Panama Canal
in the year 2000, which will benefit the Panamanian economy
directly," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary, Turkey Sign Free Trade Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Hungary signed a free trade
agreement on industrial products with Turkey here today.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, 90 percent of Hungary's industrial product
exports can enter the Turkish market tax free, while Turkey enjoys
the same preferential treatments from Hungary as granted by the
European Union countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed by Hungarian Minister of Industry,
Commerce and Tourism Fazakas Szabolos and Turkish State Minister
Ayfer Yilmaz, was a result of nearly four years of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The two nations, whose trade totaled 90.4 million U.S. dollars
in the first 10 months of 1996, agreed to realize a free trade for
all industrial products between them by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
The deal is also expected to boost mutual export of farm
products although the two countries failed to reach a farm free
trade agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
