<HEADLINE> First Large-Capacity Telecom Transmission Trunk Goes Into Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- China's first large-capacity
telecommunications transmission trunk between Wuhan, the capital
of central China's Hubei Province, and Chongqing, went into
operation at midnight on December 31.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based "People's Posts and Telecommunications News"
said that the SDH (synchronous digital hierarchy)-based optical
cable, involving an investment of 338 million yuan, has passed the
final appraisal by the Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The 1,272.7-km-long optical cable stretches across 16 cities
and prefectures, and is equipped with 27 relay stations and five
SDH systems each with a transmission speed of 622 Mb per second.
</P>
<P>
The cable will provide 24,570 telephone lines, serving as a new
backbone for the region's telecom system, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Dining Places Per Thousand Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Food has become a leading
clarion call in China's reform and opening policy.
</P>
<P>
As the country's rags-to-riches transformation has taken place,
China's food industry has dished up a fast development.
</P>
<P>
Restaurants, fast food outlets and street food stalls provide
almost 2.5 million dining places, and employ over seven million
people.
</P>
<P>
And the food industry's business volume in the first half of
1996 was 87.3 billion yuan (10.5 billion US dollars), according to
the latest statistics.
</P>
<P>
The figure registered an increase of 26.3 percent over that of
the same 1995 period, with its growth rate ranking first among the
whole country's businesses.
</P>
<P>
The statistics show that by the end of 1995, there were two
dining places for every thousand Chinese people, 1.88 more than
the figure in 1978. The industry yielded a business volume of 158
billion yuan (19 billion US dollars) in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Food has been one of China's booming industries in recent
years, and by the end of 1995, there were almost 2.5 million
dining places and 7.1 million staff employed, 21.3 and 6.8 times
over the 1978 figures.
</P>
<P>
Among the restaurants and food stalls, over 90 percent are run
by individuals, with fewer than 10 percent state or collectively
owned.
</P>
<P>
Since the reform and open-door policy was initiated in 1978,
the Chinese people have developed a special enthusiasm in the
pursuit of delicious and tasty food.
</P>
<P>
Experts claim that as more overseas tourists flock to China,
and local people show greater interest in good food, the Chinese
food industry will enjoy even further development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Budget Law Released in Kazakhstan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Kazakh government today
released the 1997 Budget Law which prescribes a revenue of 177
billion Tenge (2.4 billion U.S. dollars) and a spending of 200
billion Tenge (2.7 billion dollars) for the year.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, the state treasury is to make 32.8 billion Tenge
(0.44 billion dollars) in loans, thus registering a budgetary
deficit of 55 billion Tenge (0.74 billion dollars), about 3
percent of the Gross Domestic Product (GDP) which is estimated at
1,740 billion Tenge (23.5 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The law stipulates that 58 billion Tenge will be used to boost
production of local commodities -- 1.6 times that of last year,
while 165 billion Tenge will go to the national defense and social
security system.
</P>
<P>
However, the law decrees the nation's investment focus will
remain on industries, including metallurgy and exploitation of
oil, natural gas and minerals, on which Kazakh economy depends
heavily.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 Budget Law was approved by the Kazakh parliament last
Christmas and signed by President Nursultan Nazarbayev on December
31. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
