<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shandong Laws List Pollution Penalties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province
has passed two regulations to promote the importance of
environmental protection and encourage local officials to toughen
pollution controls.
</P>
<P>
One regulation clarifies the penalties for government officials
who violate environmental protection laws and regulations, "China
Daily" said today.
</P>
<P>
Officials can be punished for serious mistakes in comprehensive
policy-making in economic development and environmental
conservation that result in ecological damage.
</P>
<P>
If government officials do not tackle pollution problems in
their jurisdictions within a certain time, or approve projects
that aggravate pollution without authorization, they will face
administrative punishment.
</P>
<P>
If serious pollution problems occur, the responsible official
will face penalties.
</P>
<P>
Legal representatives of enterprises and units in this province
also are subject to the regulations.
</P>
<P>
The other regulation concerns regular evaluations of government
official's conservation efforts, according to the Provincial
Environmental Protection Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The evaluations will be used to determine their promotions,
demotions, prizes and penalties.
</P>
<P>
About 1,990 small factories that seriously pollute the
environment were closed in Shandong last year. About 860 factories
must resolve their pollution problems by the end of this year to
clean up major rivers in the province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
