<HEADLINE> Nagano Governor Regrets Tongue-in-Cheek Remark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The governor of Japanese city of
Nagano, the site for the 1998 Winter Olympic Games, apologized
Wednesday for a tongue-in-cheek remark about the sport of speed
skating made earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
"I was so careless that I have caused trouble to many people,"
Goro Yoshimura, who also serves as vice chairman of the Nagano
Olympic Organizing Committee (NAOC), told a regular news
conference in Nagano.
</P>
<P>
"I wish to take back the comment," he added.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Yoshimura said: "What's not interesting is speed
skating because two skaters just skate around on a track ... They
just look like whirligig beetles." 
</P>
