<HEADLINE> Russian PM Says Olympic Bid "A Matter of Honor" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin said Wednesday that St. Petersburg's bid to host the
2004 Olympic Games is "a matter of honor" for Russia, according to
local reports.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin was quoted as saying that most questions about
preparations for the Summer Games have been resolved and
conditions are in place for a Russian economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
"We descendants of Peter the Great should do the best for St.
Petersburg to be properly represented in the contest of cities,
even if the final lot is unfavorable to us," the prime minister
said.
</P>
<P>
Russia's second city is one of 11 candidate cities for the 2004
Games. The other bidding cities are Rome, Stockholm, Athens,
Buenos Aires, Cape Town of South Africa, Istanbul, Lille of
France, Rio de Janeiro of Brazil, San Juan of Puerto Rico and
Seville of Spain.
</P>
<P>
The IOC will announce its final selection in September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
