<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top 10 Teams of All Time in NBA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, Janaury 8 (Xinhua) -- Media selected the Boston
Celtics, Chicago Bulls, Los Angeles Lakers and Philadelphia 76ers
among the top 10 teams each two editions in NBA history.
</P>
<P>
According to a list compiled for the "NBA at 50" anniversary
celebration, the teams were selected in balloting among voters who
were asked to lelect their top 10 without ranking them.
</P>
<P>
The 1964-65 and 1985-86 Celtics, the 1991-92 and 1995-96 Bulls,
the 1966-67 and 1982-83 Sixers and the 1971-72 and 1986-87 Lakers
qualified for the list, as did the 1969-70 New York Knicks and the
1988-89 Detroit Pistons.
</P>
<P>
Bill Russell, Sam Jones and John Havlicek led the first of the
Boston teams, which won an East Finals from the Sixers on the way
to the NBA title.
</P>
<P>
Larry Bird led the 1986 team that defeated Houston in the NBA
Finals.
</P>
<P>
Michael Jordan dominated both of the Chicago teams on the list,
including last season's 1995-96 team that won an NBA-record 72
regular season games.
</P>
<P>
Jerry West, Wilt Chamberlain and Gail Goodrich led the 1971-72
Lakers team that won a record 33 consecutive regular season games
and had the best road winning percentage in NBA history (.816).
</P>
<P>
Fifteen years later, Magic Johnson sparked the "Showtime"
edition of the Lakers that beat Boston in the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
The 1966-67 Sixers, behind Chamberlain, started the season 46-4
and defeated the San Francisco Warriors in the NBA Finals. The
next NBA title for the franchise was by the 1982-83 team led by
Julius Erving and Moses Malone.
</P>
<P>
The 1969-70 Knicks were considered among the best passing teams
in NBA history and defeated the Lakers in the Finals behind Walt
Frazier and an inspired performance by injured centre Willis Reed,
who hobbled on to the court before Game Seven and scored the first
two baskets.
</P>
<P>
Isiah Thomas was among the leaders of the 1988-89 Pistons, who
used a three-guard rotation and deep bench to sweep the Lakers in
the Finals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
