<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Plunge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 8 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks turned sharply
lower today in heavy trading after interest rates rose toward
their highest level since late October in the bond market.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average lost 51.18 to 6,549.48. It
first surpassed the 6,600 mark Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a narrow margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with its volume reaching 556.56
million shares, up from 538.19 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
Broader measures also turned down with bonds.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 4.82 to 748.41, and
the NYSE's composite index fell 1.65 to 395.25.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 7.32 to 1,320.41, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index rose 1.09 to 576.72.
</P>
<P>
Amid worries about inflation, bonds started slipping in the
afternoon, sending the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond to 6.84
percent, up from late Tuesday's 6.78 percent.
</P>
<P>
With no major economic reports scheduled today, many investors
were nervously awaiting Thursday's reading on wholesale price
inflation and Friday's data on payroll and wage levels. Another
big jump in energy futures prices aggravated market worries,
sending bonds lower. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
