<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Consumer Credit Increases in November 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The consumer credit in the
U.S. increased by an annual rate of 7.4 percent last November,
the biggest jump since July, the U.S. Federal Reserve reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the consumer borrowing in the U.S. reached
1,190 billion dollars in the month, 7.4 percent higher than the
revised figure of 1,183 billion last October.
</P>
<P>
The revolving credit in the month grew at an annual rate of 8.5
percent to 460 billion dollars. But the biggest gain was in the
miscellaneous categories such as loans for education, travel,
boats or trailers. The consumer credit in this sector rose to
352.8 billion, 12.3 percent more than in October.
</P>
<P>
Car and truck loans increased by a small 1.5 percent to 377.7
billion dollars in the month.
</P>
<P>
Consumer borrowing in the U.S. has slowed a bit in the second
half of the year but it seems that the borrowing quickened its
pace at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts have worried that many Americans are saddled with
too much debt and will be forced to scale back their spending,
resulting in slower economic expansion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright: US Will Build Strong Relations With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of
State-designate Madeleine Albright, said today that the United
State will be working to "build a strong bilateral relationship
with China" despite the differences between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Albright told the Senate Foreign Relations Committee at her
confirmation hearing that one of U.S. priorities in Asia is to
"successfully manage our multifaceted relationship with China."
</P>
<P>
"Our goal is to expand areas of cooperation, reduce the
potential for misunderstandings, and encourage China's full
emergence as a member of the international community," Albright
said
</P>
<P>
Despite "important differences," she said, "we also have many
interests in common and have worked together on issues, including
the Korean Peninsula, crime, the global environment and nuclear
testing."
</P>
<P>
Albright said she knows U.S. policy towards China has been an
issue of controversy in Congress, "but there should be no doubt
about the importance of this relationship and about the need to
pursue a strategy aimed at Chinese integration, not isolation."
</P>
<P>
At the hearing, Albright outlined the Clinton administration's
global strategy, saying the United States will continue to build
"a new framework, adapted to the demands of a new century."
</P>
<P>
In so doing, she said, U.S. armed forces "must remain the
best-led, best-trained, best-equipped, and most respected in the
world." But it also "need first-class diplomacy," she added. She
asked Congress, which forced big cuts in foreign affairs spending
in recent years, to "invest the resources" needed to maintain U.S.
global influence.
</P>
<P>
Albright is the incumbent U.S. ambassador to the United Nations
and was nominated on December 5, 1996, by re-elected President
Bill Clinton to take the place of outgoing Warren Christopher as
the secretary of state. If she is confirmed by the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, she will become the first highest ranking
woman ever in any president's administration.
</P>
<P>
The new framework she will try to realize if she becomes the
first woman secretary of state includes "measures to control the
threats posed by weapons of mass destruction, seize the
opportunities that exist for settling dangerous regional
conflicts, maintain America as the hub of an expanding global
economy" and defend Western-style democracy, which is in no way
wholy welcomed around the world.
</P>
<P>
She stressed the center of the framework is to maintain key
alliances and relationships with U.S. allies.
</P>
<P>
The Czech-born woman said the United States must be a European
power, and NATO "must keep open the door to membership to every
European nation." She envisaged NATO's expansion this summer when
NATO invites several Eastern European states to begin negotiations
to join the organization.
</P>
<P>
The NATO expansion has met with strong objections from Russia,
which sees the Western move as a new threat to its security after
the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
Albright disclosed that President Clinton will invite Russian
President Boris Yeltsin to Washington, apparently to try to
alleviate the Russian leader's worries over the expansion.
</P>
<P>
As regards Asia, Albright pledged "U.S. commitment to regional
security" by maintaining military presence in the Western Pacific,
working with its allies, Japan and South Korea, and broadening its
diplomatic and security ties in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
She also promised to devote much of her attention this dynamic
region, which is undergoing breathtaking economic development.
</P>
<P>
Bosnia and the Middle East will be on her agenda when Albright
is confirmed to become the secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. goal in Bosnia, she said, is to continue to implement
the Dayton accords and reduce the need for an international
military presence by establishing a stable military balance.
</P>
<P>
She also urged the Israelis and Palestinians to conclude a
Hebron agreement as it will "lay the basis for future progress
toward a comprehensive settlement of the Arab-Israeli conflict."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
