<HEADLINE> Chirac Appeals for Saving of Middle East Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 8 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
today appealed to the United States, Europe and countries in the
Middle East to put together their efforts to help the Arab-Israeli
peace process go out of its present deadlock.
</P>
<P>
During a traditional new year's meeting with the diplomatic
corpse in Paris, Chirac warned that the current deadlock in the
peace process risks to bring about a renewal of violence in the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"In five years, the peace process has seen progress which was
inconceivable not long ago. But these achievements are seriously
threatened today," he said.
</P>
<P>
He asked Israel to respect its agreements signed with the
Palestinians by the Labor government of Prime Minister Yitzakh
Rabin, such as complete withdrawal of Israeli troops from the West
Bank town of Hebron and the freeze of building new Jewish
settlements on Palestinian territory.
</P>
<P>
The conservative government of Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu has refused to withdraw troops from Hebron and given the
green light to the building of new settlements, including one in
an Arab neighborhood of East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"The present impasse risks to conduce to violence, terrorism
and destabilization, which can gain ground little by little," said
Chirac, who promised that France would continue to make its own
efforts in helping push forward the Middle East peace process.
</P>
</TEXT>
