<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chretien Heads Team Canada Mission to Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Team Canada, led by Canadian
Prime Minister Jean Chretien, sets out today on its third trade
mission to Asia, this time to South Korea, the Philippines and
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, which is the largest to date, is made up more
than 350 business executives, nine of the 10 provincial premiers
and the two territory leaders.
</P>
<P>
Senior government officials predict that the mission is
expected to generate at least 1.46 billion U.S. dollars in
business during the two-week visit.
</P>
<P>
Chretien has led two Team Canada trade missions to Asia: one to
China in November 1994 and the other to India, Pakistan, Indonesia
and Malaysia in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
The two missions brought to Canadian companies a total of 259
new business deals, worth an estimated 12.64 billion U.S. dollars,
government figures show.
</P>
<P>
The members of the Canadian business delegation are expected
to complete and sign numerous contracts and agreements, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
The current mission marks the first time in three such
missions, dubbed Team Canada by Chretien in 1994, in which the
Quebec premier has participated.
</P>
<P>
The Quebec premier's involvement highlights the growing
importance of the trade missions, a cornerstone of trade policy
under the Chretien government, experts say.
</P>
<P>
"These missions are helping us to increase exports and create
jobs for Canadians. They also demonstrate what we can accomplish
when we work together," Chretien said.
</P>
<P>
Officials said the mission is expected to focus on key Canadian
sectors, such as agri-food, the environment, transportation,
energy and natural resources, and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Two-way trade of goods and services between Canada and the
three Asian countries combined totaled 6 billion dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The potential for more business with each country is
considerable, since they are among the fastest growing economies
in the Asia-Pacific region, the officials noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
