<HEADLINE> Chirac Renews Appeal for Int'l Intervention in E. Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 8 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
today renewed his appeal for the launching of an international
intervention force in the Great Lakes region in central Africa,
where the refugee crisis is far from ending and violence is
raging.
</P>
<P>
"The Great Lakes region appeals more than ever for an
international intervention. The refugee crisis there has not
ended. The destabilization forces remain threatening," Chirac
said in a traditional new year meeting with the diplomatic corps
in Paris.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his wish that "Americans and Europeans together
find a lasting solution to the human tragedy" there.
</P>
<P>
"Beyond the remarkable action of humanitarian organizations
which have to shoulder the job of a multinational force, our
states should mobilize their means and rescue hundreds of
thousands of abandoned men, women and children," said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
In a clear reference to the refusal by the United States to
back a multinational force in central Africa, Chirac said, "This
epoch is no more for the rivalries of the other age."
</P>
<P>
The United States has refused to support the dispatching of a
multinational force to eastern Zaire, despite a resolution by the
United Nations Security Council in November calling for an
international intervention to end the refugee crisis.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations International Children's Emergency Fund
(UNICEF) said today in Geneva that the number of refugees who died
in the past several days in eastern Zaire has increased
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
The daily death rate among refugees in the Lubutu region, 170
kilometers southeast of Kisangani, is now 2.1-3.8 among 10,000
people, close to those of Ethiopia and Somalia in their drought
disasters in the early 1980s and early 1990s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
