<HEADLINE> Three Iraqis Involved in Espionage for Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Three Iraqi men confessed today
that they were involved in espionage for Israel's Mossad spy
agency, the Iraqi television reported.
</P>
<P>
The televised confessions came less than three weeks after
four other Iraqis confessed that they had been working for the
American Central Intelligence Agency (CIA), which was denied by
the United States.
</P>
<P>
The three men said that they gathered and provided Iraqi
military intelligence for Israel. They said that in return, they
received a large amount of funds from Mossad, the Israeli
Intelligence Agency.
</P>
<P>
Jamal Majid Nadir, a businessman who traveled several times to
Turkey and met with Israeli agents there, admitted that he and
his two partners have served Mossad from 1995.
</P>
<P>
They attracted the Iraqi authorities' attention from the very
beginning, they said on television.
</P>
<P>
The TV report gave no indication of when the men were
arrested.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi intelligence service uncovered a spy ring working
for the CIA recently. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
