<DOCNO> XIE19970109.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zairean President to Return to France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Zairean President Sese Seko Mobutu
will return Thursday to France, where he stayed from November 4 to
December 17 last year in his private villa at
Roquebrune-Cap-Martin, southeast France.
</P>
<P>
The French embassy in Kinshasa confirmed to the AFP the issuing
of a visa to Mobutu, his wife and his entourage, but failed to
tell which date the president will leave for France.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Mobutu and his family can go to France whenever they
want. We are neither Switzerland nor the United States," AFP
quoted a French diplomat as saying in Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland refused to renew the visa of Mobutu after he had a
prostate cancer operation in the Swiss city of Lausanne in August
last year.
</P>
<P>
The United States has refused entry of Mobutu for years, except
in New York, the site of the United Nations, for a limited stay.
</P>
<P>
After he returned to Zaire in December, Mobutu set up a crisis
government, reshuffled the army leadership and made preparations
for a counter-offensive against the Tutsi Banyamulenge rebels in
the eastern Kivu region of the country.
</P>
<P>
Mobutu asked the new Zairean army chief of staff, General
Mahele Lyoko, to launch a counter-offensive, which is envisaged by
the Zairean government to be "thorough and devastating."
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the Tutsi rebels in eastern Zaire
today asked what they called mercenaries from France, Belgium,
South Africa, Angola and Togo to immediately withdraw from Zaire.
</P>
<P>
The rebels accused the mercenaries of supporting Zairean
government forces in the latters' preparations for a
counter-offensive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
